{At the beginning of the article, I will show some examples of what is NOT
Reti. Make sure to go through all these examples in order to understand the
importance of the different move orders. Reti should be played with
understanding. In Reti, we should be very careful before going for a double
fianchetto, This should be done only in specific cases.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3.
Bg2 c5 ({Another example would be} 3... e6 4. O-O ({Let's suppose that White
starts with} 4. c4 {and Black immediately goes out of book with} Nbd7 5. O-O c5
{In this case, a typical mistake would be} 6. b3 $2 ({or} 6. d3 $6) ({Of
course, White should play} 6. d4 {going for a Catalan type of play.}) 6... Bd6
7. Bb2 d4 8. e3 e5 9. d3 O-O $15 {As you can see, White has no compensation
for Black's tremendous space advantage. The b2-bishop is really awful.}) 4...
c5 5. b3 {This is another example of premature double fianchetto.} Nc6 6. Bb2
Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2 Qc7 9. c4 d4 $17 10. a3 a5 {Once again, Black has a huge
advantage.}) 4. O-O Nc6 5. b3 $2 e5 $15 {Because Reti is NOT just a double
fianchetto ... and at some moment c4.......It's a lot more than that! .........
.3 things are certain in the Reti 1. The move Nf3 2. The fianchetto of the
bishop with g3-Bg2 3. The move c4! played on the very first moves!     WHERE
SHALL WE PLACE OUR D-PAWN? When shall we play c4? Will we play b3 or not?
Where will the Bc1 be developed? Where will the Nb1 go?... on d2, on c3 , or
maybe even on a3 ????   ALL the answers to these questions depend entirely ON
BLACK'S SET-UP!!! .......Study the theory that follows!!} *

