{[%evp 0,29,27,13,13,-18,-5,-15,17,-24,-36,-13,-7,6,-7,-37,-18,-34,-30,-22,-3,
-19,-11,-11,-10,-6,-16,-12,-9,-2,7,-7] In this file, we will mainly deal with
situations where White should decide whether to play d2-d4 or d2-d3. As you
will see, in many cases, it's preferable to keep the pawn on d3.} 1. Nf3 d5 {
This move is the main topic of our camp.} ({Obviously, another important move
order is} 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ {We have reached an
important opening tabiya. You will get all the necessary theoretical knowledge
from my comments on the games featuring the Catalan setups. For the time being,
I will briefly share some of the most important positional ideas.} Bd7 {
This move is perfectly sound and is often employed at the highest level.} ({
A very important alternative is} 5... Nbd7 6. Qxc4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]
Black's idea is to proceed with ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7, thus solving the
main problem in Reti - the light-squared bishop.} 7. O-O {This is the most
precise move.} (7. d4 $2 {SUPER SOS !! THIS IS THE TYPICAL MISTAKE HERE! ...
WHILE WE STILL HAVE NOT DEVELOPED (AND BLACK WILL SOON WIN MORE TEMPI ON THE
QUEEN) ....WE BRING THIS PAWN CLOSER TO THE OPPONENT'S CAMP! ..AND IT BECOMES
A POINT OF ATTACK! ...A HOOK ! .......d4 is good for us...ONLY after we have
developed properly!} b5 8. Qc6 {This seemingly active move does not change
anything.} ({After} 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. O-O c5 {we see the problem. Black will
follow with ...Rc8, creating an annoying opposition along the c-file.} 10. Nc3
Rc8 $15 {Black's position is already better.}) 8... Rb8 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qc2 c5
$15 {[%cal Gb8c8] Black is already better since White is not prepared enough
to open the position.}) 7... b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. a4 c5 10. d3 $1 {This is the key
idea. For the time being the pawn is better placed on d4. We will play d3-d4
only when we are ready for that. A possible continuation would be} Be7 11. Nc3
Qb6 12. e4 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gc1e3] when White is ready to proceed with h2-h3
followed by Be3. This type of position is very well explained in my lecture
about Catalan setups.}) ({A very common system is} 5... c6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2
Bb7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5] Black is planning to proceed with ...Nd7 followed by ..
.c6-c5. Once again, I would suggest the setups based on d2-d3 instead of d2-d4.
} 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Nc3 ({A typical mistake would be} 9. d4 $2 {when after} c5 $15
{followed by ...Rc8 Black is already better.}) 9... a6 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black
renews the threat of ...c6-c5.} ({In case of} 9... b4 {White should transfer
his knight to the weakened c4-square.} 10. Nb1 ({Another possibility would be} 
10. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3,Ge3c4] with the idea of Ne3-c4.}) 10... c5 11. d3 Be7 12.
Nbd2 O-O 13. Nc4 {[%cal Ge2e4] White's next move will be e2-e4, restricting
Black's pieces. White should wait with the move d3-d4 until all the pieces are
activated.}) 10. a4 {[%csl Ga4,Gc3] Remember this typical construction -
Nc3+a4. The pressure on b5 makes it difficult for Black to execute the advance
...c6-c5.} ({As usual,} 10. d4 {is well met by} c5) 10... b4 {In general,
White is happy to see this move due to the newly weakened c4-square.} ({
Another possible direction would be} 10... Be7 11. Rd1 O-O 12. d3 {Once again,
we prefer to keep the pawn on d3!} Rc8 13. e4 Qb6 14. h3 {With this move,
White usually prepares the e3-square for the bishop.} c5 15. Be3 {In this type
of structure, White can definitely fight for a slight advantage. You can find
further details in the article dedicated to the Catalan setups.}) 11. Nb1 Be7
12. d3 c5 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Nc4 Rc8 15. b3 a5 16. e4 {Once again, we get the
type of position we are familiar with.}) 6. Qxc4 {At this point, Black's most
popular move is 6...c5 with the idea of ...Bc6 on the next move. Let's suppose,
however, that Black starts with} Bc6 {The problem with this move is that the
c7-pawn cannot fight for the centre. White will restrict Black's minor pieces
with the setup based on d2-d3 and e2-e4.} 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 Be7 ({Nothing
changes} 8... Bd6 {when White again plays} 9. d3 O-O 10. Nc3 e5 11. e4 $16 {
[%cal Gd3d4] Since Black's pieces are poorly placed, we can already consider
playing d3-d4.}) 9. d3 O-O 10. Nc3 b6 11. e4 Bb7 12. Rd1 $16 {Again, White has
a huge advantage. Since his pieces are more active, the advance d3-d4 is an
option.}) 2. g3 Nf6 ({When you play the Reti, it's very important to know how
to fight against the combination ...c7-c6 and ...g7-g6. Let's take a look at
some examples.} 2... c6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 ({A typical and very frequent
mistake will be} 4... dxc4 $2 5. Na3 {Now, White is going to easily recapture
the c4-pawn. Black does not have any compensation for the reduced central
control.} Bg7 ({Defending the pawn with} 5... b5 {is very well met by} 6. d3 $1
{Before playing Ne5, we should open the position as much as possible.} ({
I am not a big fan of} 6. Ne5 Bb7 7. Nxb5 {even though, White retains some
advantage.}) 6... cxd3 7. O-O ({Another possibility is} 7. Ne5) 7... dxe2 8.
Qxe2 {Black cannot survive for too long. White has a tremendous advantage in
the development.}) 6. Nxc4 Nf6 7. O-O O-O {This position is important for your
understanding of the Reti. The critical question is whether to play d2-d4 or
put the pawn on d3. We need to understand that the move d2-d4 gives White some
advantage but weakens the complex of light squares (e4 and d5). Personally, I
would play d2-d4 when the black bishop cannot go to f5. A very flexible move
would be} 8. b3 $16 ({After} 8. d4 $6 Bf5 9. b3 Be4 10. Bb2 Nbd7 {Black has
some counterplay in view of his control of the central light squares.}) ({
Another typical strategy is} 8. d3 $16 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5]
planning to launch a queenside minority attack by means of simple moves such
as Bd2, Rb1, b2-b4, a2-a4, and b4-b5. This attack is very well supported by
the g2-bishop.} Be6 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Bd2 h6 11. b4 $16 {[%cal Ga1b1,Ga2a4,Gb4b5]
White has an obvious advantage.}) 8... Nbd7 ({We always need to calculate} 8...
Nd5 {In this case, however, Black does not get any advantage of the knight
jump.} 9. Bb2 Bxb2 10. Nxb2 Nd7 11. a3 {[%cal Gd1c2]} ({Since the
light-squared bishop cannot reach the f5-square, we can consider} 11. d4 Re8
12. Nd3 $16 {with a stable advantage.}) 11... a5 12. Qc2 e5 13. Nc4 Qe7 14. d3
{This type of position is very difficult for Black. The main reason is that he
does not have favourable pawn breaks. At the same time, White can prepare the
advance b3-b4-b5 or e2-e4 followed by d3-d4.} Re8 15. Qb2 f6 16. Rfe1 N5b6 ({
If Black plays an active move such as} 16... f5 {we should be always ready to
follow with} 17. e4 $16) 17. Ncd2 $16) 9. Bb2 Nb6 10. Qc2 Nxc4 11. bxc4 Bf5 12.
d3 Ne8 13. Bxg7 Nxg7 14. Rab1 $16) 5. Qa4 $1 {A very interesting idea
threatening cxd5.} dxc4 {It's difficult to suggest a better option.} ({After} 
5... Nd7 {The symmetrical structure arising after} 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Nc3 Ngf6 8.
O-O O-O 9. d4 {is favourable for White in view of the misplaced d7-knight. The
move} Nb6 {does not improve the position of the knight because after} 10. Qb3 {
[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] White is ready to follow with a2-a4-a5.}) (5... Bd7 $6 6. d4
Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 dxc4 (8... c5 9. Qb3 $16) 9. Qxc4 $16) 6. Qxc4 Nf6 7. O-O
O-O 8. Qc2 {The exact move order is not so important.} ({White can also start
with} 8. d3 Nbd7 {Black has nothing better than this move. Magically, the
queenside knight is always misplaced in Reti. In many lines, we will see that
Black suffers exactly because he cannot find a reliable square for this knight.
} ({The exchange of the light-squared bishops by means of} 8... Be6 9. Qc2 Qc8
10. Nbd2 Bh3 {does not make Black's life simpler. White can just follow with}
11. b3 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nbd7 13. Bb2 $14 {Once again, Black's position is very
difficult because of the absence of pawn play. On the other hand, White can
slowly expand on the queenside.}) 9. Qc2 Re8 10. b3 e5 11. Nbd2 (11. Bb2 e4)
11... Nd5 12. Bb2 a5 13. a3 Qe7 14. Rfe1 Nc7 15. e3 $16 {Again, Black has no
constructive plan.} ({Another possibility would be} 15. e4 {followed by d3-d4.}
)) ({I don't prefer} 8. d4 {in view of} Bf5) 8... Bf5 9. d3 Qc8 10. b3 Bh3 {
Once again, this idea is not a problem for us.} ({The knight jump} 10... Nd5 {
does not achieve anything after} 11. Bb2 Nb4 12. Qc1 $14 {with a stable
advantage for White.}) 11. Bb2 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nbd7 ({Nothing changes} 12... Nd5
13. Bxg7 {I always take on g7 to make sure that the black king is exposed to
checks from the diagonal a1-h8.} Kxg7 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. Qxc3+ Kg8 16. b4 {
[%cal Ga2a4,Gf1c1] Again, we got the type of position we like. Black does not
have any counterplay while White can make progress on the queenside.} Nd7 17.
a4 Nf6 18. Rfc1 Nd5 19. Qb2 $16 {White enjoys a stable advantage. The advance
b4-b5 is on the agenda.}) 13. Nbd2 Re8 14. Rac1 e5 15. e4 {Gaining space and
stopping ...e5-e4 once and for all. Black's position is very difficult, mainly
due to the misplaced d7-knight.} Qc7 16. Nc4 Rad8 17. b4 a6 18. a4 {White has
an obvious advantage.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. c4 {Theoretically speaking, this is the
most precise move. It requires, however, a bit more of  knowledge.} ({As I
will discuss in the lecture about Slav setups, the lazy option is} 4. O-O {
At this point, we will restrict ourselves to the choice between d2-d4 and
d2-d3.} Bg4 5. c4 e6 ({When the light-squared bishop is already on g4 or f5,
the move} 5... dxc4 {almost never works. The reason is that Black cannot play .
..b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7 anymore.} 6. Na3 b5 {As usual, this overambitious
move backfires.} ({We already know that the structure arising after} 6... Nbd7
7. Nxc4 e6 8. d3 {is favourable for White.}) 7. Ne5 Bd7 8. d3 $1 {Before
taking on b5, White wants to open the position.} cxd3 9. Nxb5 dxe2 10. Qxe2 $18
) 6. cxd5 {This move is a very important part of White's strategy. The attempt
to get a favourable version of the Carlsbad structure} exd5 {should be
answered with} 7. d3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] White's hopes for an advantage are
connected with the advance e2-e4.} ({After} 7. d4 Nbd7 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. b3 O-O 10.
Bb2 Re8 {Black is the one who will be fighting for an advantage. The g2-bishop
is not effective against the pawn chain b7,c6,d5.}) 7... Be7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. e4 {
Sooner or later, White should play this move.} ({It's also possible to start
with} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. e4 {leading to the same type of play.}) 9... dxe4 10.
dxe4 Nbd7 11. Nc3 {As we will discuss later, this structure is favourable for
White. For the moment, I will restrict myself to pointing out the main reason
for my evaluation. While White can slowly prepare the advance of his central
majority, Black cannot use his queenside majority. Every pawn advance on the
queenside will create huge weaknesses.}) 4... dxc4 {This is the most
challenging continuation.} ({After} 4... Bg4 {White's most precise reaction is}
5. Ne5 $1 Be6 ({Clearly worse is} 5... e6 $6 {when after} 6. Nxg4 Nxg4 7. e4
Nf6 8. e5 Nfd7 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. d4 {White's space advantage and bishop pair
provide him with a nice advantage.}) 6. cxd5 Bxd5 7. Nf3 $1 {Obviously, we
shouldn't exchange the light-squared bishops. The d5-bishop is kind of
problematic. Now, our positional threat is Nc3 on the next move.} c5 $1 {
Freeing the c6-square for the bishop.} ({Worse is} 7... e6 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. O-O
Be7 10. d3 $1 {As it mostly happens in the Reti, the pawn is better placed on
d3. Now, Black should deal with the threat of e2-e4.} Bxf3 {Giving the bishop
pair but keeping a solid position.} ({After} 10... c5 $6 11. Nxd5 $1 exd5 12.
e4 $1 {White immediately opens the position in order to effectively use his
bishop pair.} dxe4 13. dxe4 O-O ({In case of} 13... Nxe4 14. Qd5 Nef6 15. Qxb7
O-O 16. Bf4 {White is dominating.}) 14. e5 $16 {White has a tremendous
advantage.}) ({After} 10... e5 11. e4 $1 Be6 {White can execute the move} 12.
d4 $16 {under more than favourable circumstances.}) 11. Bxf3 O-O 12. Bg2 Re8
13. Bd2 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] In this structure, White's main plan
is to prepare the advance b2-b4-b5. He will follow with simple moves such as
Qc2 and Rab1. Black does not have counterplay due to the lack of favourable
pawn contacts.} Bf8 14. Qc2 e5 15. Rab1 ({Another good possibility is} 15. Ne4
Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Nf6 17. Bg2 Qc7 18. b4 $16 {Once again, White has a huge
advantage.}) 15... Rc8 16. b4 $16) 8. Nc3 Bc6 9. O-O e6 10. d3 $1 {For the
time being, the pawn should stay on d3. White will play d3-d4 after some
preparation. One of the possible plans is e2-e4 followed by Qe2, Rd1 and d3-d4.
} Be7 ({Black can also try to fix the d3-pawn by means of} 10... Nbd7 11. e4 e5
{In this case, White immediately changes strategy -} 12. a4 $1 {[%csl Gc4]
[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gf2f4] The idea of this move is to secure the c4-square for
the knight. Now, White's plan is based on the break f2-f4.} Be7 13. Nd2 ({
Another option would be} 13. Nh4 O-O 14. Nf5 {with a nice advantage.}) 13...
O-O 14. Nc4 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4] The advance f2-f4 is coming. Again, Black's main
source of problems is the misplaced d7-knight. Had the knight been on c6,
Black would have enjoyed a quite decent position.}) 11. e4 $1 O-O ({We already
know that after} 11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 $1 e5 {the best move is} 13. a4 $1 O-O 14.
Nd2 Qc7 ({A typical positional mistake would be} 14... a6 {when White should
immediately play} 15. a5 $1 {Fixing Black's structure. A possible follow-up
would be} b5 16. axb6 Nxb6 17. Nc4 Nbd7 18. f4 Qc7 19. f5 Nb6 20. g4 {Black
has nothing to oppose to White's growing kingside attack.}) 15. Nc4 Nb6 16. b3
$3 {A very nice positional decision. White is ready to exchange the knights
only on his own terms.} Nxc4 17. bxc4 {The structure has changed. White
increased his central control and got the possibility to play on the semi-open
b-file.} Rad8 18. f4 ({Another option would have been} 18. Nd5) 18... exf4 19.
gxf4 $14 {White's central control gives him an obvious advantage.}) 12. Qe2 $1
{The most flexible move. White is freeing the d1-square for the rook.} Nbd7 13.
Rd1 ({The immediate} 13. d4 {was possible as well.}) 13... Rc8 ({Again,} 13...
e5 {will be answered with the typical} 14. a4 $3 Rc8 15. Nd2 $1 Re8 16. Nc4 b6
17. f4 exf4 18. gxf4 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 14. d4 cxd4 15.
Nxd4 e5 16. Nf5 $16 {White has a big advantage.}) ({Another characteristic
move is} 4... Bf5 $5 {The main disadvantage of this idea is that now the
b7-pawn is unprotected. Therefore, White's most logical move is} 5. Qb3 $3 {
putting pressure on b7 and d5. It turns out that Black cannot protect the
b7-pawn without accepting some kind of concession.} Qb6 {The most logical
continuation.} ({The move} 5... Qc8 $6 {is not very good because the queen is
poorly placed on the c-file. Sooner or later, White will bring his rook to c1.}
6. O-O e6 ({As we have already seen, the structure arising after} 6... dxc4 7.
Qxc4 e6 8. d3 $1 {is better for White since Black has no pawn play. Again, our
pawn is better placed on d3.} Be7 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 Re8 12. Bd2
{[%cal Gb2b4] White goes for his typical queenside minority attack. The
advance b2-b4 is on the agenda.} Bg4 13. b4 $3 Nb6 14. Na5 $3 {Having space
advantage, White refrains from exchanging minor pieces. Additionally, a5 is a
perfect square for the knight in this pawn structure.} Nbd5 15. Rab1 $16) 7. d3
Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1] White is ready to follow with Rac1.
Also, in many positions, Black should reckon with the idea cxd5 followed by
e2-e4.}) ({Nothing changes} 5... Qc7 6. d3 dxc4 7. Qxc4 $1 {when White gets
his favourite structure.} ({Remember that answering ...dxc4 with} 7. dxc4 $2 {
is almost always a bad idea in the Reti. We should take on c4 with a piece!}))
6. d3 $1 e6 7. Be3 $1 {The most precise continuation. Now, Black faces an
important choice.} Qxb3 {The most popular and reliable move.} ({After} 7...
dxc4 {the best move is} 8. Qxc4 $3 {taking on c4 with a piece! Remember that
after} Qxb2 9. Bd4 Qb4+ 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. Rb1 Qxc4 12. Nxc4 $16 {White has
tremendous compensation for the pawn. The pressure on b and c-files, combined
with the g2-bishop will destroy Black's queenside. At the same time, thanks to
the d3-pawn, Black's f5-bishop is out of play.}) 8. axb3 a6 9. Nc3 {This is my
favourite move.} ({An additional option is to go for the bishop pair by playing
} 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. h3 $14 {with a small but stable
advantage.}) 9... h6 10. Nd4 Bh7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc2 $3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Ge3d4]
This subtle move is a very important part of White's strategy. White will
proceed by b3-b4 followed by Bd4. After that, he can consider using the
central pawn majority. A possible follow-up would be} Nbd7 13. b4 Rb8 (13...
Bd6 14. b5) 14. Bd4 Be7 15. f4 O-O 16. O-O $14 Rfe8 17. Bh3 {White enjoys a
stable advantage.}) ({After} 4... g6 {My favourite choice is} 5. b3 $3 {
This is one of the rare cases when I go for the double fianchetto. In my
opinion, the lines with ...g7-g6 provide a very good illustration of the Reti
philosophy.} ({White can also try} 5. Qa4 $5 Bg7 (5... Bd7 6. d4 Bg7 7. O-O $14
) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 $14) 5... Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O {We have reached a very
important crossroads. This position is important not for your theoretical
knowledge but for your understanding of the Reti. That's why we shall take a
look at many different possibilities.} dxc4 {This is one of the most
principled choices. Black wants to proceed with ...c6-c5 followed by ...Nc6,
thus finding a good square for the typically problematic b8-knight.} ({
Pointless is} 7... Na6 {when White's best continuation will be} 8. d3 {Now, we
shall take a look at two possible developments of the game -} Ne8 {Simplifying
the position will not solve Black's problems.} ({Remember that after} 8... dxc4
{we always take with the b-pawn!} 9. bxc4 $1 Nc7 10. Nbd2 ({another
possibility would have been} 10. Nc3) 10... Ne6 11. Rb1 {White immediately
makes use of the semi-open b-file.} ({Another typical move would be} 11. a4 $1)
11... Ne8 12. Bxg7 N8xg7 13. Qc2 Nf5 14. e3 c5 15. a4 $14 {Black's position
remains difficult. His main problem is the development of the queenside.}) 9.
Bxg7 Nxg7 10. Nbd2 d4 11. a3 c5 12. Rb1 ({Playing in Benko style with} 12. b4
cxb4 13. Qb3 bxa3 14. Qxa3 $14 {is also possible. White has tremendous
compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Qc7 13. b4 {White has a fantastic version
of the Benoni.}) (7... Nbd7 8. Qc2 {This is the simplest way of handling the
position.} ({Another good possibility would be} 8. d4 $1 {Since the knight is
on d7, Black cannot play ...Bf5. In this Catalan type of position, White's
main idea is to prepare the advance e2-e4. A possible line would be} b6 9. Nc3
Bb7 10. Qc2 e6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qh4 $14 (14. Qe2 $14)
) 8... Re8 ({After} 8... dxc4 {we would prefer to take on c4 with a piece.
After} 9. Qxc4 Nb6 10. Qc2 Nbd5 11. a3 a5 12. d3 $14 {White enjoys his typical
advantage. Black does not have counterplay.}) 9. Rc1 {Pay attention to this
typical move. Since Black has already committed to ...Nbd7, White wants to
invade via the c-file after cxd5.} e5 ({After} 9... c5 {White's best strategy
is to open the centre with} 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. d4 $16 {In this
typical Catalan type of position, White has a huge advantage because Black
cannot develop his queenside.}) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black is forced to accept this
inferior pawn structure.} ({Even worse is} 10... cxd5 {when after} 11. Qc7 e4
12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nd4 {White is dominating.}) 11. d3 a5 12. a3 Qe7 13. Nbd2 {
Again, White is better due to the poorly placed d7-knight. A possible
continuation can be} Nf8 14. Nc4 f6 15. e4 Nc7 16. d4 {Due to the better
development and superior piece activity, White is more than ready for this
advance.} exd4 17. Nxd4 Nfe6 18. Re1 $16 {with an obvious advantage.}) ({
The exchange of the light-squared bishops does not help Black. Let's take a
look at the following example:} 7... Bf5 8. d3 $1 {When you see the black
bishop on f5, this is almost always the right choice!} Qc8 9. Qc2 $1 Bh3 10.
Nbd2 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 {Again, Black has difficulties finding a plan. At the same
time, White is ready to expand with a2-a3 followed by b3-b4.} Na6 12. a3 dxc4
13. Nxc4 $1 {When possible, we take on c4 with a piece!} ({The second best
option is} 13. bxc4) 13... Nc7 14. b4 $1 $16) (7... c5 $6 {When you see the
move ...c6-c5, the best choice is to go for a Catalan type of position after}
8. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. d4 cxd4 11. Qxd4+ Nf6 12. Rd1 {This position
is very difficult for Black because the g2-bishop is putting tremendous
pressure on the queenside.} ({Another possible direction is} 12. Qb2 $5 Nc6 13.
Nc3 Kg8 14. Rfd1 Qb6 15. Na4 Qa5 16. Rac1 Bf5 17. Nc5 $16) 12... Qxd4 13. Nxd4
$16 {It's not clear how Black will develop his queenside.}) (7... Bg4 8. d3
Nbd7 ({The type of position arising after} 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 e6 10. Nd2 Ne8 11.
Bxg7 ({White can also play} 11. d4) 11... Nxg7 12. b4 Nf5 13. e3 {is in
White's favour because the black knights don't have favourable squares. At the
same time, White can organize the break b4-b5. The attempt to close the
position by means of} d4 {does not solve Black's problems. For example, after}
14. e4 Ne7 15. Nb3 e5 16. Bg2 Nd7 17. Bh3 $14 {White is calling all the shots.
He is ready to proceed with f2-f4. In this structure, c4-c5 is also an option.}
) 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 ({After} 12... cxd5 13. e3
$1 $14 {White is better because of the bishop pair and the misplaced d7-knight.
Black would have preferred to have a knight on c6. A possible follow-up would
be} Rc8 14. Rc1 a6 15. Rxc8 Qxc8 16. Qa1 $1 Qb8 17. Rc1 $16 {when Black is
under huge pressure.}) 13. Qc2 $1 Rc8 14. a3 c5 15. Nd2 $14 {White is slightly
better.} ({The Hedgehog setup is also possible. For example, after} 15. e3 b6
16. Rac1 Qe7 17. Rfe1 $14 {White is obviously slightly better.})) ({A
principled approach is} 7... a5 {planning to follow with ...a5-a4. Therefore,
White's most logical move seems to be} 8. Nc3 $1 Ne4 (8... Na6 9. d4) (8... d4
9. Na4) 9. Na4 $1 {This is the key idea. In the following lines, I will
demonstrate an important idea that you should remember.} Bxb2 ({An alternative
is} 9... Na6 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. d3 Nec5 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Qc2 dxc4 14. Qxc4 $1 {
We don't forget to take on c4 with a piece.} Nd7 15. b4 $3 axb4 16. Qxb4 {
[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gf3d2,Gd2c4] In this structure, our final goal is to lose
the a-pawn and win Black's b and c pawns in return. The arising endgames with
an extra pawn (5 vs 4) are usually winning for White. In the beginning, White
puts pressure on the b-file and also tries to win queenside space by means of
a2-a4-a5.} Nf6 (16... e5 17. a4 Qa5 18. Rfb1 $14) 17. a4 Nd5 18. Qb2+ Kg8 19.
Rfc1 {White keeps his slight advantage.}) 10. Nxb2 d4 11. Nd3 {An important
idea. Now, it's not easy for Black to support the d4-pawn. The following line
is quite possible -} Na6 12. a3 Nec5 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. b4 Ne6 15. d3 Bd7 16.
Qd2 $16 {White has a stable advantage.}) 8. bxc4 c5 9. d3 Nc6 10. Ne5 $3 {
This move is a very important part of White's strategy. After exchanging the
c6-knight, he will keep putting pressure on the queenside thanks to the
powerful g2-bishop.} Nxe5 ({The alternative} 10... Nd4 {does not solve the
problems. For instance, after} 11. e3 Ne6 12. Qc2 Nd7 13. Nf3 Bxb2 14. Qxb2 Rb8
15. Nc3 $16 {It's clear that Black has huge problems.}) 11. Bxe5 Ne8 12. Bxg7
Nxg7 13. Nc3 Ne6 14. Rb1 Rb8 15. Qa4 a6 16. Rfd1 (16. Nd5) 16... Bd7 17. Qa3
Re8 18. e3 Qc8 19. Nd5 $16 {Black is completely busted.}) 5. O-O {Starting
with this move is important.} ({After the immediate} 5. Na3 {Black can just
play} b5) 5... Nbd7 {This is the most precise move. The idea is to answer 6.
Na3 with 6...Nb6.} ({Obviously, after} 5... g6 $6 6. Na3 Bg7 7. Nxc4 O-O 8. b3
$1 (8. d4 Bf5) 8... Bf5 9. Bb2 {We achieve one of our favourite types of
position.}) ({Useless is} 5... Bf5 $6 {when the game might continue} 6. Na3
Nbd7 7. Nxc4 e6 8. d3 $1 {Once again, putting the pawn on d3 is the best
decision.} h6 9. h3 (9. e4) 9... Be7 10. e4 Bh7 11. Qe2 {White has an obvious
advantage since Black is playing without his light-squared bishop.}) ({Also
after} 5... Bg4 $2 {White's typical reaction is} 6. Na3 b5 7. Ne5 Qb6 8. Nxg4
Nxg4 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 $18 {Black's position is almost resignable.}) ({
We have already pointed out that the immediate is well met by} 5... b5 6. d3
cxd3 7. Ne5 dxe2 8. Qxe2 $16) 6. Na3 Nb6 $1 {This is the only correct
continuation.} ({After ...Nbd7, the move} 6... b5 {does not work in view of} 7.
Nd4 $1 ({White can even start with} 7. d3 $1) 7... a6 8. d3 $16 {Black will
soon collapse.}) ({The overambitious} 6... e5 $6 7. Nxc4 e4 8. Ng5 $1 Nc5 {
backfires after the precise} 9. d4 $3 exd3 10. Ne5 Be6 11. b4 Ncd7 12. Nxe6
fxe6 13. Nxd3 $18 {Black is positionally lost.}) ({In case of} 6... e6 7. Nxc4
Be7 {White can play} 8. d4 {because the black light-squared bishop bishop
cannot reach f5.}) ({We already know that the type of position arising after} 
6... g6 7. Nxc4 Bg7 8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 {is favourable for Black.}) 7. Qc2 Be6 {
The critical continuation.} ({The alternative way of defending the pawn} 7...
Qd5 {is worse since the queen is exposed on d5. White should play} 8. b3 $1 Bf5
9. Qc3 cxb3 ({Black is not ready for an active play after} 9... Ne4 10. Qe3
cxb3 11. axb3 Nf6 12. Nc4 {White's piece activity gives him tremendous
compensation for the pawn. A possible line would be} Nxc4 13. bxc4 Qxc4 14.
Rxa7 Rxa7 15. Qxa7 $18 {when White is winning.}) 10. axb3 Qd8 11. Nc4 {White
better development and piece activity promise sufficient compensation for the
pawn. The game might continue} Nbd5 12. Qb2 e6 13. d3 Bg6 14. Nfe5 {with an
advantage for White.}) ({We know that the structure arising after} 7... g6 8.
Nxc4 Bg7 9. b3 $1 O-O 10. Bb2 $14 {is better for White.}) ({Nothing changes} 
7... Bg4 8. Nxc4 Nxc4 9. Qxc4 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e6 11. d3 $16 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gb2b4,
Ga1b1,Gb4b5] White got his thematic advantage. The idea is to prepare the
advance b2-b4-b5.}) 8. Re1 {I like this tricky move designed to overprotect
the important e2-pawn. The threat is Ng5 on the next move.} ({The main line
goes} 8. Ng5 Bg4 9. Nxc4 Bxe2 {We can now see why it's important to
overprotect the e2-pawn.} 10. Ne5 Bh5 11. Re1 {The arising positions are very
complicated. I provide detailed coverage in the lecture featuring the Slav
setups.}) 8... h6 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 g6 11. e4 Bg7 12. d4 O-O 13. Bb2 a5 (
13... a6 14. Nc4) 14. Nc4 Nxc4 15. bxc4 $44 {White has decent compensation for
the pawn. I analyze this position in the lecture about the Slav setups.} *

