{In this chapter, we will examine some more examples when Black plays ...dxc4.
Obviously, there will be some common themes with the previous file.} 1. Nf3 d5
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. c4 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Na3 Nb6 7. Qc2 {In this position,
Black's most common move is 7...Be6. This continuation is covered in the
lecture dedicated to the Slav setups.} g6 {This is a move that you will often
face when playing against inexperienced opponents.} 8. Nxc4 Nxc4 ({In the
previous example, we have seen that after} 8... Bg7 $6 9. b3 $3 {White is
better.}) 9. Qxc4 Bg7 10. d3 ({Another option is} 10. b3 Nd5 11. Rb1 O-O 12.
Bb2 Bxb2 13. Rxb2 {when White is better since Black has no counterplay in this
pawn structure.}) 10... O-O 11. Bd2 {This move indicates White's intention of
organizing a minority attack by means of b2-b4-b5.} Be6 {[%cal Gd8c8,Ge6h3]
Black is planning to exchange the light-squared bishops by means of ...Qc8
followed by ...Bh3. As we know, however, this exchange is not dangerous for
White.} 12. Qc2 ({Another possibility would be} 12. Qc1 {with the idea of
exchanging the dark-squared bishops via h6. A possible follow-up would be} Nd5
13. Bh6 Rc8 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 {and now} 15. b4 $3 {Since the black king is exposed
on g7, we can execute this idea without spending time on preparation.} Kg8 16.
a3 a5 17. bxa5 $1 {In general, exchanging these pawns is favourable for White.}
Qxa5 18. Nd4 Bd7 19. Qb2 Qa7 20. Rfc1 $16 {White has an obvious advantage.})
12... Qc8 13. b4 Bh3 14. Rab1 ({White can also consider exchanging his
dark-squared bishop for the knight by means of} 14. Bc3 {when a possible
follow up would be} Re8 15. Bxh3 Qxh3 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Rab1 Qd7 18. Rfc1 {
In this position, Black's bishop is completely useless. White can proceed with
his queenside play.}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Re8 16. Rfc1 e5 17. e4 $1 {Remember
this typical idea. White prevents ...e5-e4 and fixes the e5-pawn which is now
a target.} Qd7 18. Bc3 Nh5 19. h3 ({Obviously, premature is} 19. a4 {in view of
} Nf4+) 19... Rad8 20. Rd1 Bf6 21. a4 Ng7 22. Qb2 $16 {White has a huge
advantage.} *

