{In this instructive example, I will show White's best reaction to ...Bf5.} 1.
Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. c4 Bf5 5. O-O {There is nothing wrong with this
typical move.} ({In my opinion, however, even more precise is} 5. Qb3 $3 Qb6 ({
Once again, the move} 5... Qc8 {is not favourable for Black. White can continue
} 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d3 e6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Rac1 {As always
happens, the opposition on the c-file is very annoying for Black.} Qd7 12. Ne5
{Another important move in White's strategy. Besides opening the c-file, White
prepares the advance e2-e4.} Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Rac8 14. e4 dxe4 15. dxe4 Bg6 16.
Rfd1 {White is almost winning.}) 6. d3 Nbd7 {The knight is not very well
placed on d7. Now, White can already consider cxd5.} ({As we have already seen
in the previous examples, after} 6... e6 {the most precise reaction is} 7. Be3)
7. Qxb6 $3 {With the black knight being on d7, this exchange works quite well.
The next move is cd5.} axb6 ({Another option is} 7... Nxb6 {Nevertheless, after
} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nc3 {the black knight is still misplaced on b6. A possible
follow-up would be} e6 10. Nh4 $1 {White is going after the bishop pair.} ({
The alternative} 10. Be3 $1 {is also very strong.}) 10... Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4
Bg6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bf4 $16 {with an obvious advantage.}) 8. cxd5 $3 Nxd5 ({
After} 8... cxd5 9. Nc3 {We can see that Black has no compensation for the
damaged queenside structure.}) {At this point, a very important positional
idea to remember is} 9. Nd4 $3 (9. e4 $2 Nb4) 9... Bg6 10. Bxd5 $3 {You can
easily miss this move if you don't know it in advance. Now, White gets access
to the important b5-square.} cxd5 11. Nb5 Rc8 12. N1c3 e6 13. Be3 $16 {[%cal
Ge3d4,Gf2f4] White enjoys a typical structure. After Bd4, followed by f2-f4,
he can actually play on both wings.}) 5... e6 6. cxd5 exd5 ({Of course, after} 
6... cxd5 {White will play} 7. Qb3 $1) 7. d3 Be7 ({Nothing changes} 7... Nbd7 {
White should just follow the familiar strategy -} 8. Nc3 $1 Be7 9. Qc2 O-O 10.
e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 Bg6 12. Nh4 Re8 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. f4 $16 {with a big
advantage.}) 8. Nd4 {This is another way of preparing e2-e4.} ({My preference
would be} 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Qc2 {with the following possible line:} O-O 10. Nc3
Nbd7 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Nh4 $16 {when White
gets his typical huge advantage.}) 8... Bc8 9. Nc3 $5 ({Even more precise
could have been} 9. e4 $1) 9... c5 ({After} 9... O-O {White is ready for the
thematic} 10. e4) 10. Nb3 Be6 {This structure is also favourable for White.
Black cannot easily neutralize the pressure generated by the powerful
g2-bishop.} 11. Bg5 $5 Nbd7 {Black wants to recapture on f6 with a knight. In
this way, both c5 and d5-pawns will be protected.} ({Clearly worse is} 11...
Nc6 $2 {in view of} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. e4 $5 d4 14. Nd5 $16 {with a huge
advantage for White.}) 12. e4 $1 d4 ({We know that the structure arising after
} 12... dxe4 13. dxe4 {is very difficult for Black. The advance ...c6-c5
weakens an entire complex of squares.}) 13. Ne2 Qb6 14. Qc2 {[%cal Gb3d2,Gb2b3]
After neutralizing Black's queenside play, White is ready to put his kingside
majority in motion. The next two moves will be Nd2 and b2-b3.} O-O ({Better
would have been} 14... Bxb3 $1 {but still, after} 15. axb3 O-O 16. f4 Rfe8 17.
Bxf6 $1 Nxf6 18. Bf3 {White is better. The advance e4-e5 is already on the
agenda.}) 15. Nd2 Rac8 16. b3 $1 ({A decent alternative would have been} 16.
Nf4 $1 h6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. a4 $3 {[%cal Gb2b3] Immobilizing
Black's queenside majority is our first priority.} b6 20. b3 $1 {[%cal Gh2h3,
Gf2f4] White is ready to advance his kingside pawns.}) 16... h6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6
18. Nf4 $14 {White has a stable advantage. Later on, Ninov managed to win the
game.} Nd7 (18... Bd7 19. e5 Ne8 20. Nc4 $3 (20. Nd5 Qd8) 20... Qa6 (20... Qd8
21. Bxb7) (20... Qc7 21. Nd5) 21. a4 $16) 19. Nxe6 (19. Nc4 $1 Bxc4 (19... Qa6
20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. a4 Ne5 22. f4 Nxc4 23. bxc4 (23. Qxc4 Qxc4 24. bxc4 $16 a5
25. Rab1 Rb8 26. e5 b6 27. Bd5 Bd8 28. Kg2 Bc7 29. h4 Rfe8 30. h5 $18) 23...
Qd7 24. e5) 20. bxc4 $18 (20. dxc4 $18)) 19... Qxe6 20. f4 (20. a4) 20... b5
21. a4 a6 22. Ra2 $5 Nb6 (22... Nb8 23. e5 Nc6 24. Bxc6 Qxc6) 23. axb5 axb5 24.
Ra6 Rc6 25. Rfa1 Rfc8 26. Qd1 c4 27. bxc4 bxc4 28. e5 c3 29. Bxc6 Rxc6 30. Nf3
c2 31. Qc1 Qb3 $1 $132 (31... Qd5) 32. Ne1 Bb4 33. Rxb6 Rxb6 34. Qxc2 Qe6 35.
Nf3 Bc3 36. Ra8+ Kh7 37. Ra2 Qc6 38. Kf2 Qb7 39. Qe2 Qd7 40. Qe4+ g6 41. Kg2
Kg7 42. Re2 Qa4 43. g4 Qd1 44. f5 Rb1 45. e6 Qf1+ 46. Kg3 Ba5 47. Qe5+ Kh7 1-0

