{[%evp 0,59,24,18,14,-4,-4,4,12,-7,8,16,16,5,14,18,18,18,31,2,4,1,21,24,31,-4,
18,22,73,39,42,46,61,86,83,64,98,98,98,94,107,122,151,147,151,110,105,101,108,
103,96,95,96,97,130,131,136,132,132,124,140,130] The next three examples
feature a very important pawn structure. I explain why the kingside majority
is more important than Black's queenside majority.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 ({
Another way to get the same pawn structure is} 2... c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5.
cxd5 exd5 6. O-O) 3. Bg2 c6 4. c4 Bf5 5. O-O ({A decent alternative is} 5. Qb3
$1) 5... e6 6. cxd5 exd5 {When the white pawn is still on d2, this structure
is difficult for Black. The reason is that instead of d2-d4, White can prepare
the advance e2-e4 by means of d2-d3.} ({More precise is} 6... cxd5 $1 {
Nevertheless, after} 7. Qb3 {White can still ask some questions.}) 7. d3 Be7 8.
Qb3 $5 {Usually, the white queen goes to c2. Beforehand, however, White wants
to force the black queen into an inferior position.} Qb6 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Nc3
Nbd7 11. e4 {This is the point behind White's strategy.} Bg6 (11... dxe4 12.
dxe4 Bg6 13. Nh4 {would transpose into the game.}) 12. Nh4 $1 dxe4 ({The
structure arising after} 12... d4 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Ne2 ({Even} 14. Nb1 {
is possible}) 14... c5 15. h3 {is difficult for Black. White has a powerful
bishop pair and mobile central majority. The following line is a good
illustration of the spirit of the position.} Rac8 16. b3 {Obviously, we have
to prevent the advance ...c5-c4.} Qc7 17. a4 {White wants to immobilize
Black's queenside majority.} ({The immediate} 17. f4 {would have been possible
as well.}) 17... Nb8 18. Bf4 $1 {The idea of this move is to provoke} Bd6 ({
After} 18... Qd8 {White can follow with} 19. Bxb8 $3 Rxb8 20. f4 {After the
inevitable e4-e5, the g2-bishop will dominate. There are no stable squares for
the black knight.} Nh7 21. h4 b6 22. e5 {Remember this position! Black's minor
pieces are not playing.} Qc7 23. Kh2 $3 {[%cal Ge2g1,Gg1f3,Gf3d2,Gd2e4] A
fantastic idea! White is preparing the manoeuvre Ng1-f3-d2-e4.} Rfe8 24. Ng1
Rbd8 25. Nf3 Nf8 26. Nd2 {White's advantage is out of question.}) 19. Bd2 Nc6
20. f4 $16 {Since Black has played ...Bd6, this move comes with a tempo. White
is ready to follow with e4-e5.}) 13. dxe4 {The structure has been clarified.
Sooner or later, White's central majority will start moving. At the same time,
Black cannot push his queenside pawns because every pawn move there will
create weaknesses. Additionally, White will soon obtain the bishop pair.
Before pushing the central pawns, however, White should first stabilize the
position.} ({White could have started with} 13. Nxg6) 13... Ne5 14. Be3 Qa6 15.
Nxg6 hxg6 16. Bd4 Qd3 17. Qd1 $3 {Probably, Black underestimated this move.
White will exchange the queens on his own terms.} Qxd1 18. Raxd1 Nc4 19. e5 {
We can already start advancing the central majority.} Ng4 20. b3 Nb2 (20...
Ncxe5 $2 21. h3 $18) 21. Rd2 Rfd8 22. h3 Nxe5 23. Nd5 {White is already
winning. Later on, he easily converted the advantage.} Bd6 (23... cxd5 24. Bxe5
{[%csl Rb2]}) 24. Bxb2 cxd5 25. Rxd5 Nc6 26. Rfd1 Be7 27. Rd7 Kf8 28. Bf3 Rab8
29. Bc3 f6 30. Be4 (30. h4) 30... g5 31. Kf1 Ke8 32. Bg6+ Kf8 33. Ke2 a6 34.
Be4 Rxd7 35. Rxd7 Nd8 36. Bd2 b6 37. b4 a5 38. a3 Ne6 39. Bd5 Nd4+ 40. Kd3 Nb5
41. a4 Nd6 42. bxa5 bxa5 43. Bxa5 Rb1 44. Kc2 Ra1 45. Bb4 Ke8 46. Bc6 1-0

