1. g3 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bg4 4. O-O Nbd7 5. d3 ({Of course, our move order
will be different -} 5. c4 e6 6. cxd5 exd5 (6... Nxd5 7. d3) 7. d3 c6 8. Nc3
Be7 9. Qc2 O-O 10. e4 {when we get the desired typical position.}) 5... e6 6.
c4 ({Note that our setup does not work so well with a knight on d2, instead of
c3. The following line is a good example -} 6. Nbd2 Be7 ({Also possible is} 
6... Bd6 7. c4 c6) 7. c4 c6 ({Worse is} 7... dxc4 $6 8. Nxc4 {with a better
structure for White.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 O-O {We can now see
that the white knight is misplaced on d2. We would prefer to have it on c3.})
6... c6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 Be7 ({The move} 8... Bd6 {does not change the
character of the game. A possible continuation would be} 9. Qc2 O-O 10. e4 Re8
11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 dxe4 13. dxe4 {Once again, we have this typical structure
that is known to be favourable for White.} Qe7 14. Bg2 {White starts gradually
preparing the advance of the central pawns.} Bc5 15. Kh2 Bd4 16. Bd2 {Before
pushing f2-f4, we need to complete the development.} Rad8 {Finally, White is
ready to proceed with f2-f4.} 17. Rae1 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4] overprotecting the
important e4-pawn.}) 9. Qc2 ({Starting with} 9. h3 {is an option as well.} Bxf3
10. Bxf3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White is ready for the thematic advance e2-e4. In order
to prevent this idea, Black can play} d4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {This is
another typical structure that you should know. White is fighting for an
advantage due to his bishop pair and the possibility to organize a queenside
attack. The idea is to prepare the break b2-b4-b5. Therefore, Black's most
logical move seems to be} a5 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] Still,
White is planning to proceed with Rab1 followed by b2-b4. As explained earlier,
in this structure, White is ready to exchange his b-pawn for Black's a-pawn.}
Qb6 15. Bf3 Rfe8 16. Rab1 Bd6 17. a3 a4 18. b4 axb3 19. Qxb3 Qxb3 20. Rxb3 {
As discussed previously, White is planning to lose the a3-pawn and win Black's
b and c-pawns. A possible line would be} Nc5 21. Rbb1 Rxa3 22. Bb4 Ra7 23. Rfc1
Re5 24. Rc4 Bf8 25. Bxc5 Rxc5 (25... Bxc5 26. Bxc6 bxc6 27. Rxc5 $18) 26. Rxd4
g6 27. Rd8 $16 {Black's position is very difficult. White is planning to
follow with the advance d3-d4-d5.}) 9... O-O 10. e4 Qa5 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3
dxe4 13. dxe4 {White achieved what he wanted. Now, it's time to prepare the
advance of the central pawns.} Rfe8 14. Bg2 ({Another option would have been} 
14. Bd2 Ne5 15. Be2 {It makes sense to put the bishop here in order to control
d3 and c4-squares.} Qb6 16. Be3 Qc7 17. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5] White has an obvious
advantage. The advance e4-e5 is already on the agenda.}) 14... Ne5 15. Bf4 Nh5
16. Be3 Bc5 17. Rfe1 Bxe3 18. Rxe3 {Even though White allowed the exchange of
the dark-squared bishops, he is still better. It's not easy for Black to
prevent the idea of Qe2 followed by f2-f4 and e4-e5.} Rad8 19. Qe2 g6 20. f4
Nd7 21. e5 $16 {White has an obvious advantage. Later on, he managed to
convert it into a full point.} Nb6 22. Kh2 Kh8 23. Re1 Ng7 24. Ne4 Qxa2 25. Ra3
Qc4 26. Rxa7 Qxe2 27. Rxe2 Re7 28. Nc5 Rb8 29. Re3 Ne6 30. Nxe6 fxe6 31. Rc3
Nd5 32. Rb3 b5 33. Ra6 Rc7 34. h4 Kg7 35. Rba3 Rb6 36. Ra8 c5 37. Re8 c4 38.
Raa8 Ne7 39. Rab8 Rxb8 40. Rxb8 Rc5 41. Rb7 Kf8 42. Be4 Kf7 43. h5 gxh5 44.
Bxh7 Ke8 45. Be4 Kd8 46. Kh3 Nd5 47. Kh4 b4 48. Bxd5 exd5 49. Rxb4 d4 50. b3 d3
51. bxc4 d2 52. Rb1 Rxc4 53. Rd1 1-0

