1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bf5 5. O-O e6 6. cxd5 exd5 ({After} 6...
cxd5 {White's typical response is} 7. Qb3 {It turns out that Black cannot
comfortably defend the b7-pawn. The most logical continuation seems to be} Qb6
({The move} 7... Qc8 {is usually a bad idea because the white rook will appear
on c1. Black's problems are well illustrated by the following line -} 8. Nc3
Nc6 9. d3 Be7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Rac1 {This is the problem. The pin on the c-file
is very annoying for Black.} Qd7 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Rac8 14. e4 dxe4 15.
dxe4 Bg6 16. Rfd1 $16 {White has a huge advantage.}) 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Nc3 Nc6
10. d3 $14 {White has a slight advantage due to his better pawn structure.}) 7.
d3 Be7 8. Qb3 {I like this idea very much. Before putting the queen on the
typical c2-square White wants to misplace the black queen.} Qb6 ({As usual,
the move} 8... Qc8 {is not desirable for Black since the black queen will be
misplaced on c8.} 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 $16 {White got
a favourable version of this pawn structure due to the badly placed black
queen.}) 9. Qc2 {[%csl Rb6] Since the black queen is not optimally placed on
b6, we can now prepare the advance e2-e4.} h6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4
Bh7 13. Be3 {The inferior position of the black queen allows White to win an
important tempo.} Qa5 14. a3 Re8 15. b4 Qc7 16. Rfe1 Bf8 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Bxd6
Qxd6 19. Rad1 $16 {White has an obvious advantage.} Qe7 20. Qb3 Na6 21. e5 Nd7
22. Bh3 Nf8 23. Ne4 Bxe4 24. Rxe4 Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Nd4 g6 27. e6 f6 28.
Qc4 Rd6 29. Rg4 Kh7 30. Rh4 Rd5 31. Nxc6 bxc6 32. Qxa6 Rd1+ 33. Kg2 Rd6 34. Rc4
f5 35. Rxc6 Rxe6 36. Kg1 h5 37. Bf1 Qd7 38. Rxe6 Nxe6 39. Qb5 Qe7 40. Qd5 Ng5
41. h4 Nf7 42. b5 Nh6 43. a4 f4 44. Qg5 1-0

