{In this file game you will find a lot of analyses of the so-called
Reti-Closed Catalan.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O (4. c4 Be7) 4... Be7
5. c4 O-O 6. b3 {this is the pure Reti move...an intriguing possibility
together with 6.d4! of course!} ({Another good choice but not the subject of
this database is} 6. d4 $1 {, transposing to the Catalan Opening. White's move
order has already prevented Black's more ambitious defenses that would include
the move dxc4, as well as the lines with Bb4+.}) (6. cxd5 $6 {way too
optimistic!} exd5 7. d3 c5 (7... c6 8. Qc2 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. e4))
(6. Qc2 dxc4 7. Qxc4 Nc6 (7... Nbd7) 8. d4) 6... c5 $5 (6... d4 $5 7. e3 $1 {
I prefer this, to the most common 7.Bb2-c5 etc. The bishop mustn't be
committed to b2 yet.} c5 (7... Nc6 8. exd4 Nxd4 9. Bb2 c5 (9... Bc5 10. Ne5 $3
a5 11. Nc3 Nd7 12. Nd3 Ba7 13. Nb5 $3 Nxb5 14. cxb5 Nf6 15. Qe2 $16) 10. Na3
$14 (10. d3 $14)) 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Ne5 $1 {a very typical move in such
positions ! While it is generally desirable for the player with less space to
trade a pair of minor pieces, this active knight move's main idea is to
disturb the coordination of Black's pieces - starting with the knight b8, with
cannot move to c6 for now.} (9. Ba3 $5 {White is playing a reversed Benoni,
and it's generally desirable to trade minor pieces in Benoni positions, except
the fianchetto bishop. The queenside bishop is usually the worst piece (which
means best to trade), as it lacks perspectives in this structure.)} Nc6 $5 10.
Re1 $1 (10. Bxe7 $2 Qxe7 11. Re1 e5 $15) 10... Nd7 (10... Bxa3 11. Nxa3 Re8 12.
d3 e5 13. c5 $16 Nd5 14. Nc4 Nc3 15. Qd2 $14) 11. d3 a5 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nbd2
$132 Nc5 14. Ne4 $14 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 Qd6 16. Nd2 e5 17. Re1 Bf5 18. Ne4 {White
is better in this structure when he manages to exchange two pieces}) 9... Qc7 (
9... Nbd7 10. Nxd7 $1 Nxd7 11. d3 e5 (11... Rb8 12. Na3 $14) 12. Ba3 $1 $14 Re8
13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd2 $14 Nc5 (14... a5 15. Qe2 Nc5 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 $14 (
17. Bxe4 g6 18. Rfe1 $14)) 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Rb8 17. Qd2 $16 (17. f4 exf4
18. Rxf4 $16)) (9... Nfd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. d3 Nc6 12. Ba3 $14) (9... a5 10.
Re1 $14 (10. Na3 $1 $14)) 10. Re1 Nc6 (10... Nfd7 11. Nd3 $1 Nc6 12. Ba3 $14) (
10... Nbd7 11. Nf3 $1 {A counter-intuitive move, but now Black is forced to
protect his d4-pawn by misplacing yet another piece.} Bc5 (11... e5 $2 12. Nxd4
$18) 12. a3 a5 13. d3 {is another very pleasant Benoni position. Play might
continue:} e5 14. Nbd2 $36 h6 {Preventing Ng5.} 15. Rb1 $1 (15. Nh4 Re8 16. Ra2
Nf8 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 {, and White can easily play in the centre or on the
kingside with moves like Nf5, f2-f4, Rae2 and/or Qh5, while at the same time
having a queenside pawn majority at his disposal that can at some point move
forward.}) 15... Re8 16. b4 $36) 11. Qe2 $1 Qxe5 12. Qxe5 Nxe5 13. Rxe5 Nd7 14.
Re4 $1 {this is an excellent idea that was suggested to me by the chess author
and computer expert Nikolaos Ntirlis} Nc5 15. Rxd4 $1 Bf6 16. Bb2 Nd3 $1 (16...
Bxd4 $2 17. Bxd4 Nd3 18. Nc3 $16) 17. Bc3 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Rd8 19. Be3 $1 $36 {
white has nice pressure and a risk-free game ! ...It is easy for a computer to
hold with black, but not for a human!} e5 20. Nc3 $16) (6... dxc4 $6 {Trading
a central pawn for White's b-pawn is positionally unsound.} 7. bxc4 c5 8. Bb2
Nc6 {Black's only achievement is the active development of this knight, which
does not stay on the board for long:} 9. Ne5 $1 $16 Nxe5 10. Bxe5 {White can
easily pressure Black's queenside. His central pawns are flexible and Black
has difficulties finishing his development.} Nd7 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13.
Nc3 (13. d3) 13... Qe7 14. Rb1 Rb8 15. a4 (15. d3) 15... b6 16. a5) (6... b6 $5
7. Nc3 $1 (7. cxd5 $5 exd5 (7... Nxd5 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. d4 $14) 8. d4 Bb7 9. Nc3
Na6 10. Bb2 $14 {with a typical queen's Indian game!}) (7. Bb2 Bb7 8. e3 $5 {
a classical Reti move!} Nbd7 9. Nc3 c5 10. Qe2 Rc8 (10... Ne4 11. cxd5 exd5 12.
Rac1 $14 (12. Rfd1 Bf6 13. d4 $14)) 11. d3 a6 12. Nh4 $5 $14) 7... Bb7 8. d4
Nbd7 9. Bb2 {with a small advantage a la Catalan} c5 10. Ne1 $1 (10. cxd5 $5
Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Re1) 10... cxd4 (10... Ne4 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc2 Bf6 13.
Rb1 $5 $14) (10... Rc8 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc2 $14 Re8 13. Rc1) 11. Qxd4) (6...
a5 7. d4 $1 {the best moment to transpose to a Catalan!} (7. Nc3 $5) 7... a4 (
7... b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. Nc3 $14 Nbd7 10. Rc1) 8. Ba3 $1 axb3 9. axb3 Bxa3 10.
Nxa3 $14 b6 11. b4) 7. cxd5 $1 {I am convinced that this move is the simplest
and best!} Nxd5 (7... exd5 {This leads to a Tarrasch position which is
slightly better for White:} 8. d4 Nc6 9. Nc3 $5 (9. Bb2 $5 {and now for example
} Bf5 (9... h6 10. Nc3 Re8 11. Rc1 $14 cxd4 12. Nxd4) (9... Re8 10. Nc3 Bg4 11.
dxc5 Bxc5 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rc1 $14 Bb6 14. Na4 Ne4 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. a3 $16) (
9... Ne4 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 {with play against the isolated queen's pawn.}
Nxc3 12. Bxc3 d4 13. Bb2 Re8 (13... Bf5 14. Rc1 Qd6 15. b4 Nxb4 16. Nxd4 {
1-0 (59) Artemiev, V-Firouzja,A/chess24.com INT 2021}) 14. Rc1 Bb6 15. Qd2 $14
{[%emt 0:00:26] 1-0 (40) Svane, R-Quintiliano Pinto,R/Chess.com INT 2021/
Mega2021 Update} (15. b4 $14)) 10. Nc3 Rc8 11. Rc1 {1-0 (37) Hera,I-Nemeth,M/
Budapest 2019/CBMs}) 9... Ne4 10. Bb2 Bf6 11. Na4 cxd4 (11... b5 $2 12. Nxc5
Nxc5 13. Rc1 Nxb3 14. axb3 $16) (11... b6 12. dxc5 Bxb2 13. Nxb2 $14) 12. Nxd4
Bd7 13. Rc1 Re8 14. Nc5 $14) 8. Bb2 $1 {Now no matter what Black plays,
White's next move is d4, for example, and d4 next move!} b6 (8... Bf6 9. d4 $3
{Even now, not minding the pin. Now to prevent the tempo-winning and
space-gaining e2-e4-e5, Black has to release the tension.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 $14 {
White is better in this position. His next move can be Nc3, Nd2 or Qd2,
protecting the bishop on b2.} Nc6 (10... b6 11. e4 Ba6 12. exd5 Bxf1 13. Kxf1
$18 {1-0 (20) Grandelius,N-Halvax,G/chess.com INT 2022}) (10... Na6 11. Nc3
Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Rb8 13. Nb5 $14) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd2 $16 Nc3 14.
Ne4 $3 $18) (8... Nc6 9. d4 cxd4 (9... Bf6 10. e4 Ndb4 (10... Nc7 11. e5 Be7
12. dxc5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bxc5 14. Nc3 $16 Be7 15. Ne4 Nd5 16. Nfd2 $18) 11. a3
Na6 12. e5 Be7 13. Nbd2 Bd7 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. b4 Nd3 16. Bc3 $18) 10. Nxd4 Bd7
(10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bf6 12. Qd2 Bxb2 (12... Bd7 {is probably critical.} 13.
Bxd5 (13. e4 Bxb2 14. Qxb2 {1/2-1/2 (17) Panno, O-Sanguineti,R Buenos Aires
1968}) 13... exd5 14. Rd1 Rc8 15. Nc3 {?- (19) ? (40) Kramnik,V (2783)
-Nakamura,H (2776) Zuerich 2015}) (12... Nf4 13. gxf4 Qxd2 14. Nxd2 {1-0 (49)
Kramnik,V (2792)-Mamedyarov,S (2808) Paris 2018}) (12... Ne3 13. Qxd8 {1-0
Anton Guijarro,D-Aravindh,C/Moscow 2019/CBMs}) 13. Qxb2 {1-0 (66) Jones,
G-Safarli,E/Astana 2019/CBMs/[Jones, Gawain]}) (10... Ndb4 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12.
Nd2 Bd7 13. Nc4 Qc7 14. Rc1 {1/2-1/2 (20) Acosta,P-Liascovich,L/Montevideo
2020/CBMs}) 11. Na3 (11. Nc3 Nxc3 (11... Ncb4 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. e4 Nb4 14. e5 {
1-0 (70) Jones,G-Abdusattorov,N/Chess.com INT 2020/CBMs}) 12. Bxc3 Rc8 13. Rc1
{1-0 (25) Van Kampen,R (2615)-Wojtaszek,R (2741) Germany 2016} ({While Giri
has tried} 13. Qd3 {in a couple of blitz games.} Nxd4 14. Bxd4 {1-0 (55) Giri,
A (2785)-So,W (2815) chess.com INT 2017}) (13. e3 Bf6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Qxd8 {
1/2-1/2 (38) Petriashvili,N-Magalashvili,D/Tbilisi 2019/CBMs})) (11. Nd2 Bf6
12. Bxd5 Nxd4 13. Bxb7 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Bxb2 15. Rad1 Rb8 16. Be4 {1/2-1/2 (57)
Jakubowski,K-Bernabeu Lopez,C/Roquetas de Mar ESP 2022}) 11... Nxd4 (11... Bf6
12. Rc1 (12. Qd2 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bc6 14. Rfd1 Ne7 (14... Bxd4 15. Qxd4 {1-0 (66)
Giri,A-Leko,P/chess24.com INT 2020/CBMs}) 15. Bxf6 Qxd2 16. Rxd2 gxf6 17. Bxc6
{1/2-1/2 (41) Artemiev,V-Nakamura,H/chess24.com INT 2020/CBMs}) (12. Nc4 Nxd4
13. Bxd4 {1/2-1/2 (41) Artemiev,V-So,W/chess24.com INT 2021}) 12... Nxd4 13.
Bxd4 Bc6 14. Nc4 Nb4 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qd2 {1/2-1/2 (47) Rapport,R-Dominguez
Perez,L/Dortmund 2019/CBMs}) 12. Qxd4 Bf6 13. Qd2 {Jones, Gawain: 'see 10...
Bd7.'} Bc6 14. Rfd1 (14. Nc4 Bxb2 (14... Ne7 {was played against the American
last time he essayed the line.} 15. Bxf6 Qxd2 16. Nxd2 {?- (21) ? (43)
Nakamura,H (2749)-Merario Alarcon,A (2405) Caleta 2019}) 15. Qxb2 {Compared to
the game Black has managed to develop his light-squared bishop but White still
has a nibble.} b5 16. Ne5 Bb7 {0-1 (77) Nakamura,H (2777)-Karjakin,S (2773)
Saint Louis 2018} 17. Rac1 $14) 14... Qe7 15. Bxf6 {1-0 (55) Bok,B-Van Foreest,
L/Maastricht 2019}) 9. d4 Bb7 10. dxc5 $3 Bxc5 11. Nc3 (11. Nbd2 Nd7 12. Rc1
Rc8 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Qd4 N7f6 15. Ne5 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 {1/2-1/2 (45) Oparin,
G-Smirnov,P/chess.com INT 2020/EXT 2021}) 11... Nxc3 (11... Nd7 12. Nxd5 Bxd5
13. b4 $1 {, making tactical use of the Bishop's position on b2. ?-? (38)
Artemiev,V-Nepomniachtchi,I/Warsaw POL 2021}) 12. Bxc3 {White has better
development and ideas like b3-b4-b5, followed by a knight transfer to c6.} Qe7
13. Qc2 Nd7 $2 14. b4 Bd6 15. Rad1 $16 1/2-1/2

