[PlyCount "45"]
[EventDate "2020.03.17"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.09.16"]

1. Nf3 (1. c4 {is another move order.} e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 dxc4) 1...
Nf6 (1... d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 {would be our regular Reti Move order})
2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ c6 6. Qxc4 b5 (6... Nbd7 $6 {after this
move black can no longer plat b5, and he has a problem developing the
queenside properly!} 7. O-O Be7 (7... b5 8. Qxc6) 8. d4 $1 (8. d3 O-O 9. Qc2
Re8 10. Nbd2 (10. Nc3 e5 11. Rd1 Bf8 12. e4 Nc5 13. h3 $1 Ne6 14. Ne2 Nd4 15.
Nexd4 exd4 16. Nh2 $16 {[%cal Rf2f4]})) 8... O-O 9. Nc3 $16 {with a typical
and big Catalan advantage} (9. Rd1 $16)) (6... g6 $2 {Is not a good
combination with e6.} 7. O-O Bg7 8. d4 O-O 9. Nc3 b5 10. Qb3 Bb7 11. Rd1 Nbd7
12. Bf4 $16) 7. Qc2 Bb7 8. a4 $1 {by putting pressure on the b5 point, we want
to prevent black from playing c6-c5, unless he wants to play b5-b4 first, and
then c6-c5, ..but that would offer white a nice square on c4!} (8. d4 $6 {
It is premature, because it transposes to a favourable version of Catalan.}
Nbd7 9. Nc3 a6 10. O-O c5 $132 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bg5 Rc8 13. Qd2 Qb6) 8... a6 (
8... b4 $2 {Is a strategic mistake when White's knight is still on b1. Now he
will occupy the c4 square with an overwhelming advantage.} 9. d3 c5 10. Nbd2
Nbd7 11. O-O Be7 12. Nc4 (12. a5 {Is another good way for White to continue}
Rc8 13. e4 O-O 14. Nc4 Ba6 15. h3 $16) 12... O-O 13. e4 a5 14. h3 Nb6 15. Nfe5
$16) 9. Nc3 $1 {Preventing c6-c5 by putting pressure on b5. to prevent c5} Nbd7
(9... c5 10. axb5 $16) (9... b4 10. Nd1 (10. Ne4 $1 {this is also very good!})
10... c5 11. Ne3 Nc6 12. O-O Be7 13. Nc4 O-O 14. d3 Rc8 15. a5 $14) 10. O-O Be7
(10... Rc8 $6 {this move is well known to be a bit inaccurate, and the
computer immediately points out the move 11.Rd1! for white...intending to
either go for d2-d4! or d2-d3! , depending on black's plan !} 11. Rd1 $1 (11.
d3 $5) 11... Be7 12. d4 $1 O-O (12... b4 13. Ne4 $1 c5 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. dxc5
Qa5 16. Be3 $1 Bxc5 (16... Ng4 $2 17. Bd4 Bxc5 18. Qd2 $18) 17. Bxc5 Rxc5 (
17... Qxc5 $2 18. Qxc5 Rxc5 19. Rac1 Rxc1 20. Rxc1 O-O 21. Ne5 $18 {too many
weaknesses on the queenside with all these a6-b5-b4 moves...and black cannot
keep them all!!} Rc8 22. Rxc8+ Bxc8 23. Nc6 Kf8 24. Nxb4 $18) 18. Qd3 O-O 19.
Nd4 $1 Bd5 (19... Bxg2 $4 20. Nb3 Qb6 21. Nxc5 $18) 20. Bxd5 Rxd5 21. Nc6 $3
Qc5 22. Rdc1 $3 $14) 13. Ne5 $1 $16 Nxe5 (13... Qb6 14. Nxd7 $1 Nxd7 15. Be3 c5
16. d5 $16) 14. dxe5 Nd5 15. Ne4 c5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nc3 $1 $16 {White is
much better.}) 11. Rd1 $5 (11. d3 $5 O-O 12. e4 Rc8 (12... Qb6 13. a5 $3 Qa7 (
13... Qd8 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. d4 Rc8 17. Qd3 $14) 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nxd5
cxd5 16. Be3 Bc5 17. d4 $16) 13. h3 $5 {mentioned by Alexander Delchev} b4 (
13... Qb6 14. Be3 c5 15. axb5 axb5 16. b4 $14) (13... h6 14. Be3 Ne8 15. Rfd1
$14) 14. Nb1 c5 15. Nbd2 $14) 11... O-O 12. d3 (12. d4 $5) 12... Qb6 (12... Rc8
13. e4 e5 14. h3 b4 15. Nb1 c5 16. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Rd2c4]}) 13. e4 c5 (13...
Rac8 14. Be3 c5 (14... Bc5 15. d4) 15. h3 $1) 14. h3 $1 {SUPER SOS !!! Be3
usually meets Qb6, but before that we should stop Ng4. The idea is also to
provoke b5-b4 and later to maneuver the knight Nb1-d2-Nc4 followed by Nfd2 and
f4.} Rac8 15. Be3 b4 16. Nb1 Qc7 17. Nbd2 e5 (17... Nb6 18. a5 Nbd7 19. Nc4) (
17... Nb8 18. Rac1) 18. Nc4 a5 19. Nfd2 Nb8 (19... Ba6 20. f4) 20. f4 (20. Nb3
$1 Nc6 21. Rac1 (21. Nxc5) 21... Nd4 22. Bxd4 cxd4 23. Qe2 $16) 20... Nc6 21.
Rac1 Nd4 22. Bxd4 exd4 23. Nb3 $16 {With an overwhelming position on both
flanks} 1-0

