1. c4 {our move order is of course 1.Nf3-d5 2.g3-Nf6 3.Bg2-e6 4.c4-dc4 5.
Qa4+-Nbd7 6.Qxc4-c5 7.Qb3! etc} Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7
6. Qxc4 c5 $1 (6... Be7 $2 {very passive and slow! ..now we have time for d4!}
7. d4 (7. O-O $5 O-O (7... c5 8. d4 $16) 8. d4 $1 $16 c5) 7... O-O 8. O-O c5 9.
Rd1 $16 {black cannot develop his queenside !}) (6... a6 $1 {SOS ! ..THS IS
EXACTLY THE SAME WITH 6...c5} 7. Qb3 $1 (7. d4 $2 b5 8. Qc6 Rb8 9. Bf4 Bb7 $3
$36) 7... c5 (7... b5 $2 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. Nxf7 Kxf7 10. Bxd5 $18 exd5 11. Qxd5+
Kg6 12. Qxa8) 8. a4 Qc7 (8... Rb8 9. a5 $1 $14 Bd6 10. d3 Bc7 11. Bd2 $16) 9.
d3 $1 Be7 (9... c4 10. Qxc4) 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 (11. a5 $16) 11... b6 12. e4
Bb7 13. h3 Rac8 14. Bf4 e5 15. Be3 Rfe8 16. Nd2) (6... Bd6 7. d4 $1 (7. d3 $5
a6 (7... O-O 8. O-O e5 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Nc3 c6) 8. Qb3) 7... O-O 8. O-O e5 9. Qc2
$3 Re8 (9... e4 10. Ng5) 10. Nc3 c6 11. Rd1 $3 (11. e4 $14) 11... Qe7 12. e4
$16) 7. Qb3 $1 {Black intended to play a quick b7-b6 and Bb7, which Ne5 can
now meet.} (7. O-O b6 $1 $132) 7... Rb8 $1 {SUPER SOS ! ...BLACK ALSO NEEDS TO
KNOW WHAT HE IS DOING! ... THESE GOOD MOVES LIKE 7...Rb8! and b6 etc etc..are
not to be taken for granted because many players will the Black pieces will
not know them and play randomly. Black is preparing b7-b5. Now I prefer:} (7...
Bd6 $6 8. d3 $1 (8. O-O $1 a6 9. a4 (9. d4 $5 O-O 10. Be3 $1 $14) 9... Rb8 10.
a5 $3 {it is always good to fix the queenside with a5..if we can protect this
pawn !} Bc7 11. Qa3 $3 O-O 12. d3 Qe7 13. Nbd2 $16) 8... Rb8 9. a4 a6 $2 (9...
Bc7 10. Bd2 $1 Ba5 $2 11. Bxa5 $1 Qxa5+ 12. Nc3 $14) (9... b6 10. Na3 {
transposes}) 10. a5 Bc7 11. Bd2 O-O 12. O-O $16 Nd5 13. Rc1 $16 (13. Nc3 $16
Nb4 14. Ne4 Bxa5 15. Bg5 f6 16. Be3 $1 $16) 13... b6 (13... Qe7 14. Na3) 14.
axb6 Bxb6 (14... Rxb6 15. Qa3 $16) 15. Qa3 Bb7 16. Nc3 $16) 8. a4 b6 $1 (8...
a6 $6 9. a5 $1 Bd6 10. d3 O-O $6 {this is even worse , because now we even
have time for Nbd2-Nc4 !} (10... Bc7 11. Bd2 O-O 12. O-O {, it is clear that
Black is running out of useful moves first. White on the other hand can
continue Rc1 or even protect a5 one more time with Qa4, followed by Nb1-a3-c4.}
b5 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. Qc2 $16) 11. Nbd2 $1 Bc7 (11... b5 12. axb6 Nxb6 13. O-O
Bb7 14. e4 $16) 12. Nc4 b5 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. O-O Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Qe7 16. b3 Bb7
17. Ba3 $16) 9. d3 Bd6 (9... Bb7 $5 10. O-O Bd6 11. Na3 {transposes}) 10. Na3
a6 (10... Ba6 $4 11. Nb5 Bxb5 12. axb5 $18 {[%cal Ra1a7,Rg2a8]}) 11. O-O O-O
12. Nc4 Bc7 13. Bd2 {SUPER SOS ! ...if black knows what he is doing, and he
doesn't allow us to fix the queenside with a4-a5,or reach a favorable version
of the Catalan with a passive Be7?- d4! , we will reach this position! ..which
is the basic one for us..in the Catalan-Reti ...our plan is Bd2-Rfc1 and
Qa3-b4! or Qc2-b4! , or Qd1-Qe1 !? and b4! In all these lines, we will often
consider the move e2-e4 as well ! .......CONCRETE THEORY IS NOT SO IMPORTANT
HERE...WHAT MATTERS ARE THE TYPICAL PLANS AND THE IDEAS ! Here are some..
sample lines!} Bb7 (13... b5 $2 14. axb5 axb5 15. Na5 $16 Bxa5 16. Bxa5 Qe7 17.
Bc7 $1 Rb7 18. Bf4 $16) 14. Rfc1 $1 (14. Qa3 $1 Nd5 (14... Qe7 15. Rfc1 (15. b4
) 15... Rfc8 16. b4 $36) 15. e4 Ne7 16. b4 $14 Nc6 17. b5 $5 (17. bxc5 bxc5 18.
a5) 17... axb5 18. axb5 Nce5 19. Nfxe5 Nxe5 20. Bc3 $3 Nxc4 21. dxc4 $14) (14.
Qc2 $5 Rc8 (14... Nd5 $6 15. e4 Nb4 16. Bxb4 cxb4 17. d4 Rc8 18. Qe2 Nf6 19. e5
$3) (14... a5 {prevents b2-b4 but is a major concession on the light squares.}
15. e4 {It is important to prevent Nd5. Now White has many constructive moves
to prepare to play in the centre (d3-d4) or on the kingside  (f2-f4), while it
is hard to suggest anything other than sit and wait for Black.}) 15. Rfc1 Nd5
16. Qd1 h6 17. Qe1 $1 {1/2-1/2 (54) Maghsoodloo, P-Erigaisi,A/Sitges 2019/CBMs/
[,AeUiico]}) 14... Qe7 (14... Nd5 $5 15. Qc2 $1 {protecting e4 point..
after an eventual d3-d4}) (14... e5 15. e4 $1 h6 16. Qc2 Re8 17. b4 $14) (14...
Ba8 15. Qa3 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Ne3 $5 $14) 15. Qa3 $5 (15. Qd1 $5 Rfd8 16.
Qe1 Nd5 (16... h6 17. b4) 17. e4 Nb4 18. Bxb4 cxb4 19. d4 $1 $14) 15... Nd5 (
15... a5 16. e4 e5 17. Qb3) (15... Rfc8 16. b4 $14) 16. d4 Rfc8 17. dxc5 bxc5
18. Ne1 Nb4 $2 19. Bxb7 Rxb7 20. Bxb4 $1 cxb4 21. Qf3 Rbb8 22. Nd3 e5 23. Nd2
$14 Nf6 24. Rc4 {'!'} (24. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 25. Qxe4 $14) 24... Bb6 25. Rac1 Rd8 26.
Ne4 a5 (26... Ne8 27. b3 a5 28. Rc6 $16 g6 29. g4 $3 $16) 27. Nxf6+ Qxf6 28.
Qe4 $16 (28. Qxf6 gxf6 29. Kg2) 28... Re8 (28... Rxd3 29. Qxd3 Qxf2+ 30. Kh1
$16 g6 31. Qf3) 29. Kg2 g6 30. Rc6 Qe7 31. h4 $3 f5 32. Qc4+ Qf7 33. h5 Qxc4 (
33... gxh5 34. Qxf7+ Kxf7 35. Rh6 Kg7 36. Rxh5 e4 37. Nf4) 34. R1xc4 Kf7 35.
Rd6 e4 36. Nf4 g5 37. Nd5 Bd8 38. Rcc6 Rb7 39. Nf6 Rh8 40. Nd7 Re8 41. Nf6 Rh8
42. Rd5 Rc7 43. Ra6 Bxf6 44. Rxf5 Ke7 45. Rfxf6 Re8 46. Rh6 Kf8 47. Rxa5 Rc2
48. Rxh7 Kg8 49. Raa7 1-0

