1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxc4 c5 7. O-O $1 {
this is a rare but very interesting variation...with typical Reti ideas!
Please note that 7.0-0! and 7.Nc3! will lead to the same position! ......It is
interesting to note that although we are in the Reti Catalan, the positions
which we will get are quite often very similar with a line of the Reti-Slav! :
1.Nf3-d5 2.g3-Nf6 3.Bg2-c6 4.c4-Bg4 5.Ne5-Be6 6.cd5-Bxd5 7.Nf3-c5 8.Nc3-Bc6 9.
0-0 and d3-e4-Qe2 etc etc} (7. Nc3 $1) ({The most common move at this point is
} 7. Ne5 $5 {, taking the pair of bishops immediately but also resolving some
of Black's development problems.}) 7... Bc6 8. Nc3 a6 $1 (8... Nbd7 $6 9. e4 $1
{White's idea is to play d2-d4, either immediately or after a preparatory
Qc4-e2.} a6 $2 {now black is almost lost...and this is a mistake that many
players will commit !} (9... Be7 10. Qe2 e5 {This is an interesting move to
keep White from executing his plan, but not without its drawbacks. Black has
severely weakened the light squares d5 and f5. The game could now continue} ({
After:} 10... O-O 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 {White will take on c6 and keep a very
stable long-term advantage.}) (10... Qb6 {prevents d2-d4 but leaves the queen
misplaced.} 11. d3 O-O 12. a4 $14 {, followed by Nf3-d2-c4.}) 11. a4 O-O 12. d3
Rc8 {, and White has the pleasant choice between} 13. Nd2 ({or} 13. Nh4 {
, provoking Black to create even more weaknesses.}) 13... Re8 14. Nc4 b6 15. f4
{with serious pressure in the centre and on the kingside.}) 10. d4 $1 $16 {
White already has a huge advantage, as taking e4 is not possible:} Nb6 (10...
Nxe4 $4 11. d5 Nd6 12. Qe2 $18) 11. Qe2 cxd4 12. Rd1 Bc5 13. Be3 $16 (13. e5
Nfd7 14. Ne4 $16)) (8... Be7 9. e4 $1 (9. Rd1 O-O 10. e4 Nbd7 11. Qe2 e5 12. a4
Re8 13. d3) (9. d4 $5 {even this is a good try for a small advantage!} cxd4 10.
Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 O-O 12. Rd1 Qc8 13. Qxc8 Rxc8 14. Be3 Nbd7 15. Ndb5 {
White is tiny better due to his more active pieces and the weakness of the
d6-square.}) 9... O-O 10. Qe2 Nbd7 (10... Qb6 11. d3 Nbd7 12. a4 Rac8 13. Nd2
$14) 11. d4 $16 {With an overwhelming advantage.}) 9. e4 b5 10. Qe2 b4 11. e5
$1 {IF YOU MEMORIZE THESE LINES, MOST LIKELY YOUR OPPONENT WON'T MAKE IT OUT
OF THE OPENING!} Nd5 {THIS is the best move..but still white seems to be
better!} (11... Nd5) (11... Nfd7 $2 12. Ne4 Be7 13. Rd1 (13. d4 $5 Bb5 14. Qc2
Bxf1 15. Kxf1 $40) 13... Bb5 14. Qe3 Nc6 15. Nd6+ $3 Bxd6 16. exd6 O-O 17. d4
$16 c4 18. Ne5) (11... Ng8 $2 12. Ne4 $3 Bb5 13. Qd1 $1 (13. Qe3 $1 Bxf1 14.
Kxf1 $16 {we have tremendous compensation for this exchange!}) 13... Bxf1 14.
Qxf1 Nc6 15. d4 $3 $18) (11... bxc3 $2 12. exf6 cxb2 $2 (12... Bb5 13. Qe4 Bxf1
14. Qxa8 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 c2 (15... gxf6 16. dxc3) 16. b3 gxf6 17. Bb2 Bg7 18. Rc1
) 13. Bxb2 gxf6 14. Rfd1 (14. Rfe1 $16) (14. d4 $1 $18 Bb5 15. Qe3 $1 Bxf1 16.
Rxf1 $18 Bg7 (16... Nd7 17. d5) (16... Nc6 17. d5) 17. Nh4 Ra7 18. d5 $18)
14... Be7 (14... Ba4 15. d4 Bxd1 16. Rxd1 Be7 17. d5 exd5 18. Nh4 (18. Bxf6))
15. d4) (11... Ng4 $6 12. Ne4 $1 Bb5 13. Qd1 Bxf1 14. Qxf1 Nc6 (14... Be7 15.
d4 cxd4 16. h3 Nh6 17. Bxh6 gxh6 18. Qc1 $3 $16) 15. d4 cxd4 16. Bf4 $18 Be7
17. h3 Nh6 18. Rc1 $18 Rc8 (18... Qb6 19. Nfd2 $18) 19. Qxa6) 12. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5
13. d4 $1 c4 14. Be3 Nd7 15. Nd2 $16 *

