{In this lecture I am explaining how to handle the so-called Reti-Slav
positions. In my opinion, the most principled reply for Black is 4...dxc4. In
the analyses you will find a lot of interesting ideas. My main goal is to
teach you the typical positional and tactical ideas, so I am not trying to
give you forcing lines until move 30. Instead of that after examine the
analyses and the model games, you should be able to start "feeling" the
positions.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 (2. c4 $1) 2... d5 3. Bg2 c6 4. c4 $1 {SUPER
SUPER SOS !! DO NOT FORGET! The best move in this position is 4.c4. If you
want an easy way to play this position then you can first castle on move 4 and
then play c4 on the next move and possibly cd5! next! with all the typical
ideas that we know! However if Black knows this sequence 4.0-0-Bg4! 5. c4-e6 6.
cd5!-Bxf3! 7.Bxf3-cd5! The idea is that the game is about equal, maybe 
slightly better for White with the pair of bishops! .} (4. O-O $5 Bg4 $1 {
This is the strongest move here. Black is ready to take the knight in an
appropriate moment.} (4... g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. b3 $5 O-O (6... Ne4 7. d4 O-O 8. Bb2
Bf5 9. e3 Nd7 10. Nbd2 $14) 7. Bb2 {transpositions}) 5. c4 $1 e6 (5... dxc4 $2
{This move is not very well connected with 4...Bg4 or Bf5.} 6. Na3 g6 (6... b5
7. Ne5 Qb6 8. Nxg4 (8. d3) 8... Nxg4 9. d3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 $18 {[%cal Rg2a8]}) 7.
Nxc4 Bg7 8. b3 $16 (8. d3 $16 O-O 9. Bd2 Nbd7 10. b4 $16 (10. Rc1 $16) (10. Na5
$16))) 6. cxd5 Bxf3 $3 {This is the right time to exchange the knight. The
bishop pair is not such an important factor in the symmetrical structure.} (
6... exd5 7. d3 Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 9. e4 $14 (9. Qc2 $14)) (6... cxd5 7. Ne5 (7.
Qb3) 7... Bh5 8. Nc3 $1 Nbd7 9. d4 $14) 7. Bxf3 cxd5 $1 (7... exd5 $2 8. d3
Nbd7 9. Qc2 $16 (9. e4)) 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d4 Be7 10. e3 (10. b3 $14 O-O 11. Bb2
Rc8 12. e3) 10... O-O 11. Bd2 $14 Rc8 12. Rc1 Ne8 13. Na4 $14 {Probably White
has a tiny edge, but Black's position is very solid.}) 4... dxc4 {Maybe the
most topical line in the Slav Reti ! Some factual knowledge is required now!
DO NOT FORGET THAT YOU CAN AVOID THIS LINE, USING THE 4.0-0 and 5.c4! move
order ! Without theory, but with typical Reti play!} (4... Bf5 $5 5. Qb3 $1 {
this is probably the best move here... although 5.0-0 followed by cd5 (the
lazy man's play) is also good!} (5. O-O $5 {Is the easier way to handle the
position.} e6 6. cxd5 $1 exd5 (6... cxd5 {Black wants to stabilize his
position and to continue with Nc6. White should hurry and play} 7. Qb3 Qb6 (
7... Qc8 {The queen is misplaced here and White can easily take the initiative.
There are always some tactical possibilities on the c-file} 8. d3 Nc6 9. Nc3
Be7 (9... Bd6 {runs into} 10. Nb5 Bb8 11. Qa3 $16) 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Rac1 Qd7 12.
e4 (12. Ne5 {or})) 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. d3 $14 {The endgame is quite plesant for
White and he can push for a win without risk. The pawn on b6 is not easy to
defend, and also White has an idea to open the position by means of e2-e4. The
f5-bishop, is not a very good piece, it is quite passive and very often is
attacked by Nd4 or e2-e4.}) 7. d3 {Intending to play e4 sooner or later} Be7 (
7... Na6 $5 {is also possible, but I don't like it} 8. a3 $5 Nc5 9. Nd4 $5 Bg6
10. b4 Ncd7 11. e4 $40 {Black is behind in development and White uses this}) 8.
Qb3 Qb6 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. e4 $14) 5... Qb6 (5... Qc8 {After this
move, White has an easy play. He should continue with d3-Bf4-Rfc1, etc...} 6.
d3 e6 (6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 $1 (7. dxc4 $2)) 7. O-O $1 (7. Nh4 $1 $14 Bg6 8. Nxg6
hxg6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Nd2 Bc5 11. Nf3 $16) 7... Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. cxd5 cxd5 (
