{In this lecture I am explaining how to handle the so-called Reti-Slav
positions. In my opinion the most principled reply for Black is 4...dxc4. In
the analyses, you will find a lot of interesting ideas. My main goal is to
teach you the typical positional and tactical ideas, so I am not trying to
give you forcing lines until move 30. Instead of that after examining
carefully the analyses and the model games you should be able to start
"feeling" the positions.} 1. c4 c6 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg2 Bg4 5. O-O Bxf3
$2 {This move is quite premature, now White enjoys the advantage of the bishop
pair. A rule is that Black can exchange the bishop only when the structure is
already determined.} (5... dxc4 6. Na3 b5 7. Ne5 Bd7 8. d3 $16) 6. Bxf3 dxc4 $2
{and the very typical mistake !} 7. Na3 $16 Qd4 {This is too much, now Black
is much worse.} (7... e5 {is not solving the problems either} 8. Nxc4 e4 9. Bg2
b5 (9... Nbd7 10. d3 $1 exd3 11. Qxd3 Be7 12. Nd6+ $16 (12. Bf4 O-O 13. Rfd1
$18)) 10. Ne3) (7... e6 8. Nxc4 Nbd7 9. d3 (9. d4 $16 {This setup also
promises White an advantage, but I prefer 9.d3 because is more flexible.}) (9.
b3 $16) 9... Be7 10. Bd2 O-O 11. b4 $16 {White has a very easy play: Qb3, Rfc1,
Rab1, b5, etc..}) 8. Qc2 Na6 9. Nxc4 e6 10. d3 Nd5 11. a3 {Black has no
outposts for the knights. The position is strategically winning for White
already.} Be7 12. e4 Nf6 13. Be3 Qd8 14. b4 (14. d4) 14... O-O 15. Na5 $18 Qd7
16. Rac1 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Ne8 18. d4 Rac8 19. Qa2 Nd6 20. Bg2 h6 21. f4 b6 22. Nc4
Nxc4 23. Qxc4 Nb8 24. Qb3 b5 25. Rc2 a5 26. bxa5 Qa7 27. d5 Qxa5 28. Rdc1 exd5
29. exd5 c5 30. Qd3 c4 31. Qf5 Bc5 32. Bxc5 Rxc5 33. Be4 g6 34. Qh3 Kg7 35. f5
Nd7 36. fxg6 fxg6 37. Qe6 Nf8 38. Qe7+ Kh8 39. Rf2 Rcc8 40. Rcf1 Qb6 41. Kh1
Kg8 42. Rf7 Qd4 43. R1f6 Re8 44. Rg7+ Kh8 45. Qf7 Qxe4+ 46. Kg1 Qd4+ 47. Kg2
Re2+ 48. Kh3 1-0

