{[%evp 0,47,19,27,26,-27,55,40,32,-19,0,-1,17,2,-7,-38,-18,-28,-17,-3,11,-41,
-17,-15,0,8,10,11,35,8,6,-2,69,50,112,49,83,89,160,56,65,57,129,121,135,92,88,
89,79,84] In the so-called triangular system! Black is in a hurry to play
d5-c6, get the bishop out and strengthen his center with e6. We plan to play
all these moves without a fast Nf6: c2-c4! Followed by cxd5!. If Black follows
with cxd5 by we should try to attack fast on the queenside with
Qb3-Nc3-Bf4-Rc1 etc. If exd5, we follow the d3 -e4! Strategy with or without
the Qb3-Qb6-Qc2 motif} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bg4 (3... Bf5 {Is another
serious option. When the c8-bishop leaves c8-square, we should react with c4}
4. c4 $1 e6 (4... dxc4 $2 {Is not a good combination with Bf5. White easily
gets an advantage after:} 5. Na3 Nd7 (5... b5 6. Nxb5 (6. d3 cxd3 7. Ne5) 6...
cxb5 7. Nh4 Nd7 8. Nxf5 $16) (5... e5 $5 {is the top engine choice, but White
is still better.} 6. Nxc4 $1 (6. Nxe5 $4 {runs to a typical tactic.} Bxa3 7.
bxa3 Qd4 $1 $19) 6... e4 7. Nfe5 $3 {and it seems that all tactics work well}
Be6 (7... Nd7 8. Ne3 $16 {and White wins the e-pawn}) (7... f6 8. Ne3 Be6 9.
N5c4 $16) 8. Qc2 $1 f6 9. Ng4 $3 $14 b5 10. Na3 f5 11. Ne3 Nf6 12. O-O Be7 13.
d3 $1 exd3 14. exd3 $16) 6. Nxc4 e6 7. O-O Ngf6 8. d3 Be7 (8... Nb6 9. Qc2 $16
(9. b3)) 9. h3 $1 (9. Bd2 $1 O-O 10. b4 Nb6 11. Na5) 9... h6 10. e4 Bh7 11. Be3
Nc5 12. Nce5 O-O 13. Rc1 Ncd7 14. Nc4 Nb6 15. Na5 Qc8 16. a3 Rd8 17. Qc2 Nbd7
18. b4 $16) 5. cxd5 $1 (5. Qb3 $1 Qb6 6. d3 Nd7 7. Be3 (7. Nh4 $1 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5
9. g4 Bg6 10. O-O $14) 7... Bc5 8. Bxc5 Nxc5 9. Qc3 $14 Nf6 10. b4 Ncd7 11.
Nbd2 a5 12. a3) 5... exd5 (5... cxd5 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3
$14) 6. O-O (6. Qb3 Qb6 7. Qc2 Bxc2) 6... Nd7 7. d3 (7. Qb3 Nc5) 7... Ngf6 8.
Nc3 Be7 (8... Bd6 9. e4) 9. Nh4 (9. Qc2 O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 Bg6 (11... Bg4
12. h3 Bh5 13. Be3) 12. Nh4) 9... Bg6 (9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nf5) (9... Be6
10. e4) 10. Qc2 O-O 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Nc5 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. Bf4
(15. Be3 Ng4) 15... Qc8 16. h3 Nh5 17. Be3 Ne6 18. Rac1 (18. e5)) 4. c4 $1 {
As I already said. We should immediately attack the centre.} e6 (4... Nf6 5.
Ne5 (5. O-O $5 e6 6. cxd5 Bxf3 $1 (6... exd5 7. d3 Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3 $14 (
9. e4)) (6... cxd5 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nc3) 7. Bxf3 cxd5 8. d4) 5... Be6 6. cxd5 Bxd5
7. Nf3) (4... dxc4 $2 {This is not a good combination with Bg4.} 5. Na3 Nd7 (
5... b5 $2 {Black can't defend the pawn.} 6. Ne5 Bd7 7. d3 $1 cxd3 8. Qb3 (8.
Qxd3) (8. O-O $18 dxe2 9. Qxe2) 8... e6 9. Nxb5 $18 {And Black can resign.}) 6.
Nxc4 e6 7. O-O Ngf6 8. d3 $16 {This is the dream position for White, because
White has a free hand in the centre and can decide how to continue. The main
plan is to create weaknesses on the queenside by means of b4-b5.} Be7 9. Bd2 (
9. b3) 9... O-O 10. b4 $1 c5 (10... Nb6 11. Na5 Qc8 12. Rc1 Nbd5 13. Qb3 Rd8
14. Rfe1 $16) 11. b5 $14 {[%cal Rg2b7]}) 5. cxd5 $1 exd5 (5... cxd5 $4 6. Qa4+
Nc6 7. Qxg4 $1) (5... Bxf3 $1 {Is the only good way to continue} 6. Bxf3 cxd5
$1 (6... exd5 $2 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Qc2 Be7 10. e4 $16 dxe4 11. dxe4 O-O
12. Nc3 Ne5 13. Be2 {[%cal Rf2f4,Re4e5] followed by advancing the pawns on the
kingside.}) 7. d4 (7. d3) 7... Nc6 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. e3 O-O 11. b3 Rc8
12. Bb2 $14 {Probably White has a tiny plus here, but Black is super solid.})
6. Qb3 (6. d3 $5 {with typical play in the center. HERE ARE SOME SAMPLE LINES}
Nf6 (6... Qc8) 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 {White is ready for the e2-e4 break} Bd6 {
The bishop is not very well placed on d6 in this structure.} (8... Be7 9. e4
dxe4 10. dxe4 O-O 11. Nc3 $14 Qc7 (11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 Qc7 14. Kg2
(14. Bf4)) 12. h3 Bh5 13. Nh4 Bg6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17.
f4 Qc5+ 18. Kh2 Qe7 (18... Rfe8 19. Rad1) 19. e5 Nh7 20. Ne4 $18) 9. e4 dxe4
10. dxe4 O-O 11. Nc3 $16 Qe7 (11... Ne5 12. Nxe5 (12. Nh4 $14) 12... Bxe5 13.
h3 (13. Be3 $16 Qc7 14. f4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Rfe8 16. Bd4) 13... Be6 14. Be3 $16)
12. h3 Bh5 13. Nh4 (13. Be3) 13... Bg6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Be3 $16 (15. Bg5) (15.
f4 $16)) 6... Qb6 (6... Qc8 {The queen is very passive here and there are
always some tactical possibilities on the c-file.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3 Be7 9. Qc2
O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 Bh3 12. Nc3 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nbd7 14. Bf4 Nh5 15. Be3
Nhf6 (15... a5 16. Nd4 Nhf6 17. h3 Re8 18. Rae1 Nc5 19. f4 Bf8 20. Bf2 $14) 16.
h3 $14) 7. Qc2 {We provoke Qb6, later Be3 could come with a tempo.} Nd7 8. O-O
Ngf6 9. d3 Be7 10. e4 dxe4 (10... d4 {Is a strategic mistake and White is much
better after:} 11. Nbd2 $16) 11. dxe4 O-O 12. Nc3 Rfe8 13. Be3 Qc7 (13... Bc5
14. Na4) 14. h3 Bxf3 (14... Bh5 {is well met by} 15. Nh4 Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17.
f4 Bc5 18. Bxc5 Nxc5 19. e5 Nfd7 (19... Nh5 20. Kh2) 20. Kh2 Ne6 21. Ne4 Nd4
22. Qf2 c5 23. Nd6) 15. Bxf3 Ne5 16. Be2 Rad8 17. Rad1 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19.
Kg2 Rxd1 20. Qxd1 Qd7 21. Qxd7 Nexd7 22. f4 Bc5 23. Kf3 Bxe3 24. Kxe3 $18 *

