1. Nf3 (1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Ned2) 1... d5
2. g3 Nd7 {Preparing e7-e5 without blocking the c-pawn.} 3. d4 {Now White
would like to play some kind of Catalan in which the early knight development
to d7 would be slightly premature.} (3. Bg2 $6 e5 4. d3 Ngf6 5. O-O c6 6. c4
dxc4) 3... Nb6 {This is Black's idea, preventing c2-c4.} (3... e6 4. Bg2 Ngf6
5. c4 c6 6. Qc2 {This is a very typical Closed Catalan position in which Black
doesn't quite equalise.}) 4. Nc3 $1 {Changing the character of play. Black has
spent two moves to prevent c2-c4, so it makes a lot of sense to switch plans
and aim for e2-e4.} (4. Bg2 {There is also nothing wrong with normal
development.}) 4... Nf6 (4... Bf5 {Preventing e2-e4, but White can exploit the
exposed position of the bishop.} 5. Nh4 {It is important to attack the bishop
before Black can play h7-h6.} e6 {This is considered Black's best move here.} (
