1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {If Black chooses this move-order, it
makes a lot of sense to play for a reversed Grunfeld. This is a very dynamic
opening and White can hope to make good use of the extra tempo in most lines.}
({Of course it is also possible to play a reversed King's Indian with} 4. O-O {
, but here Black can rather easily choose a quiet line like the Exchange
Variation or the Torre Attack, where the extra tempo may turn out to be less
relevant.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $6 {With colours reversed this is the main
move, but a tempo down this sharp choice leads to problems for Black, who
cannot sustain his pawn centre.} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 Be6 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Bg5 {
To avoid losing a pawn, Black already needs to make a concession.} e4 (9... Bb4
{was probably the lesser evil.}) 10. cxd5 ({Even stronger is} 10. Qa4 $1) 10...
cxd5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. O-O Bg7 13. Qa4+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Rfd1 Kc6 $2 (
15... f5 {was the only move that offered Black some drawing chances.}) 16. Rac1
$18 Rad8 17. Nxe4+ Kb6 18. Nc3 d4 19. Na4+ Ka5 20. Nc5 Bd5 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22.
Rxd4 Rxd4 23. Nb3+ Kb4 24. Nxd4 f5 25. e3 a5 26. a3+ 1-0

