1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 Nf6 5. O-O cxd4 (5... Bg4 {is another line
where the extra tempo can be put to very good use.} 6. Ne5 cxd4 7. Nxg4 Nxg4 8.
e4 (8. e3 Nf6 9. exd4 e6 {is acceptable for Black.}) 8... Nf6 9. exd5 Nxd5 10.
c3 e6 11. cxd4 Be7 12. Nc3 $16 {Black cannot maintain the structure. After
taking on c3 or accepting a trade on d5, White will be able to put the bishop
pair to good use.}) 6. Nxd4 e5 $6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 Be6 9. Nc3 Rc8 10. cxd5
cxd5 11. Bg5 $6 (11. Qa4+ {was the better move here, winning a pawn for
insufficient compensation:} Qd7 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. Rd1 Bc5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15.
Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5+ Ke6 $14) {Now the game was less clear and Anand managed to
outplay his opponent after} 11... d4 12. Ne4 Be7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. f4 f5 15.
Nf2 e4 16. g4 Rg8 17. Kh1 e3 18. Nd3 Rxg4 19. Bf3 Rg6 20. Ne5 Kf8 21. Rc1 Rh6
22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Rg1 Bf6 24. Nd3 Rg6 25. Qa4 Qb6 26. Rc1 Be6 27. Rc6 Qb8 28.
b4 Kg7 29. Qc2 Be7 30. Qb2 Bf6 31. a4 Bd7 32. Rc5 Bxa4 33. b5 Qb6 34. Rxf5 a6
35. Qa2 Bxb5 36. Ne5 Qe6 37. Qc2 d3 0-1

