1. g3 d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O e5 5. d3 f6 (5... Nf6 6. e4 d4 7. a4 Be7
8. Na3 {In the reversed King's Indian Petrosian, White can make good use of
his extra tempo. But he needs to play very precisely. For example after} Bg4 {
Wite must immediately push away the bishop with} 9. h3 ({Bad is for example} 9.
Bd2 Nd7 10. h3 Be6 $15 {, and having reached this ideal configuration of his
pieces, Black is already better.}) {Now} 9... Be6 10. Ng5 Bd7 11. f4 {is good
for White.}) 6. c4 d4 7. e3 dxe3 (7... Bd6 $6 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Nbd2 {The bishop
will be exposed after White plays Ne4.}) (7... Be6 {is probably Black's best
choice:} 8. exd4 cxd4 9. a3 a5 {Now White needs to make useful waiting moves,
for example} 10. Re1 (10. Nbd2 $6 {is considered a positional mistake in the
Samisch, as it allows Black to easily develop his kingside:} Nh6 11. Re1 Be7
12. Ne4 Nf7 $15) 10... Qd7 11. Qa4 Ra6 {Now the extra tempo seems to work
against White, who is running out of useful waiting moves.}) 8. Bxe3 Bd6 9. Nc3
Nge7 10. Ne4 b6 11. b4 cxb4 12. d4 Bf5 13. dxe5 Bxe4 14. exd6 Nf5 15. Bf4 O-O
16. Re1 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nfd4 18. Qd5+ Kh8 19. Be3 Nc2 20. Qxc6 Rc8 21. Qd5 Qd7
22. Be4 Nxa1 23. Bf5 Qa4 24. Bxc8 Nc2 25. d7 Rd8 26. Re2 Qxa2 27. Bc1 Qa4 28.
Qf7 1-0

