1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {Against most of Black's setups,
White has a wide choice between different plans: e2-e4, c2-c4 and also the
less common c2-c3, a2-a3, b2-b4.} f6 ({After} 5... h6 6. c4 {is a good
continuation, to enter a Benoni or Benko type position:} d4 7. e3 (7. b4 cxb4
8. a3 bxa3 9. Qa4)) 6. Nc3 {The reversed Panno system looks like a good choice
against the Samisch setup.} Be6 7. a3 ({Also interesting is the sharp pawn
sacrifice after} 7. e4 d4 (7... Nge7 {is the safer choice.}) 8. Nd5 Nge7 ({
Of course not} 8... Bxd5 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Nxe5 $18) 9. c4 dxc3 10. bxc3 Nxd5
11. exd5 Bxd5 12. Re1 $44) 7... Nge7 8. Rb1 Ng6 {After Black has prevented
b2-b4 for the moment but released control of d5, White now plays} 9. e4 dxe4 (
9... d4 $6 10. Nd5 Nge7 11. c4 dxc3 12. bxc3 $16 {, and the rook on b1 enters
the game very effectively.}) 10. Nxe4 (10. dxe4 {should be better, securing
the d5-square for the knight.}) 10... Qd7 11. Re1 Rd8 12. h4 Be7 13. b4 cxb4
14. axb4 Nxb4 15. h5 Nf8 16. h6 Kf7 17. hxg7 Kxg7 18. Qd2 Nc6 19. Qh6+ Kf7 20.
Ba3 Rg8 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Rxb7 Qxb7 23. Qxf6+ Ke8 24. Nxe5 Qc7 25. Nxc6 Rg6 26.
Qxd8+ Qxd8 27. Nxd8 Kxd8 28. Ra1 Rg7 29. Nc5 Bc8 30. d4 Rc7 31. c4 Ke7 32. f4
Kf6 33. Kf2 Ng6 34. Ne4+ Kg7 35. Nd6 Bd7 36. c5 Ne7 37. Be4 h5 38. Rh1 a5 39.
Rxh5 Ra7 40. Rh7+ Kg8 41. Rxe7 a4 42. Bd5+ Kh8 43. Nc4 1-0

