1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 Bg4 5. Ne5 Bf5 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 (7. dxc5
$3 $16 {This move would just be bad a tempo down, but with the bishop already
on g2 it works tactically:} e5 (7... e6 8. Be3 $1 Nf6 (8... Qb8 9. b3 {This is
an old theory line which is considered good for Black with colours reversed.
Needless to say, the extra tempo Bg2 further increases Black's problems, who
is behind in material and in development.}) 9. O-O Ng4 (9... Nd7 {and just
fortifying his extra pawn on c5:} 10. b4 ({Now White has the pleasant choice
between playing dynamically:} 10. c4 Bxc5 (10... Nxc5 11. Nc3 Be7 12. Rc1 Rc8
13. b4 Nd7 14. cxd5 exd5 15. b5 $18) 11. Bxc5 Nxc5 12. Qd4 $16) 10... a5 11. c3
Be7 12. Nd2 axb4 13. cxb4 Bf6 14. Nf3 Bxa1 15. Qxa1 O-O 16. Nd4 {, with more
than sufficient compensation for the exchange.}) 10. Bd4 e5 11. h3 exd4 12.
hxg4 Bxg4 13. Qxd4 Be6 14. c4 $16 {Again White's extra tempo is crucial.}) (
7... Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Qxc5 9. e4 dxe4 10. O-O $16 {, with a big lead in development.
} ({Or} 10. g4 Bg6 11. Qe2 $16)) 8. c4 Bxc5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Qxd5 $16 {, with
a healthy extra pawn.}) 7... e6 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. O-O Rc8 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6
12. cxd5 exd5 13. e4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 Be7 15. Re1 Be6 16. Bxc6+ Rxc6 17. Qa4 O-O
18. Qxc6 Qxd4 19. Rad1 Qg4 20. Nd5 Bg5 21. f4 Rc8 22. Qb7 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 Bf6 24.
Kg2 Bd4 25. h3 1-0

