1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 Be6 {This
interesting continuation was recently tested a few times in high-level games.}
8. Nc3 {I believe this is the most consistent way of handling the position.
White sacrifices a pawn for his strong pawn centre.} (8. Ng5 Bf5 9. b3 {
Mamedyarov, S (2772)-Paravyan,D (2629) Moscow 2019} a5 10. Ba3 Na6 {, and
Black has nothing to worry about.}) 8... dxc4 {Of course, only this can
justify Black's last somewhat artificial move.} (8... Ne4 {Petkov,M - Pechac,
J Terme Catez 2022} 9. Bf4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Rb1 b6 12. e4 $36) 9. e4 Na6
{The knight is moving towards d3 - a standard way to achieve counterplay in
such positions.} (9... Qc8 {makes some sense since Black keeps control of h3.
On the other hand, the queen on c8 is placed awkwardly.} 10. Qe2 Rd8 (10... Na6
11. Ng5 Nb4 {, as in Bachmayr,P - Eckerl,U Bayern 2004 , can be well met by}
12. e5 $1 $146 Nfd5 13. Nxe6 Qxe6 14. Qxc4 Nxc3 {Black definitely should try
to simplify matters.} 15. Qxc3 Na2 16. Qe3 Nxc1 17. Raxc1 {Despite the major
simplifications, White retains a definite positional advantage because the Bg7
is out of play and there are ideas of expanding with f2-f4-f5 or b4-b5.}) 11.
Rd1 Na6 {was played in Foisor,S - L'Ami,A Astana 2013. As usual, White should
have acquired the bishop pair:} 12. Ng5 $146 Nb4 13. e5 Nfd5 14. Nxe6 Qxe6 15.
Qxc4 $14) ({Too slow is} 9... h6 10. Qe2 Na6 11. Rd1 Qc8 12. Ne5 {, which let
White regain the pawn and retain all his merits in Cazzaniga,W - Bemporad,F
Corsico 2009}) 10. h3 {White isn't in a rush - by making this move he secures
e3 for his bishop and restricts the mobility of Black's minor pieces.} Nb4 11.
Be3 a5 {A vital move - Black's setup on the queenside is getting stable.} ({
Another natural try might be} 11... Qd7 $5 $146 12. Kh2 Rad8 13. Qe2 Ne8 (13...
Nd3 $6 14. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne8 16. f4 $16) 14. Rad1 Qc8 15. Ng5 $44 {
White has interesting play for the pawn - f2-f4 will follow soon.}) 12. Qe2 Qc8
13. Kh2 Ne8 ({Dubious is} 13... Rd8 $6 14. Ng5 $1 Bd7 15. Qxc4 {White was much
better in Giri,A - Dubov,D chess24.com INT 2021}) 14. Ng5 Nd6 15. f4 f5 {
This was practically forced - otherwise Black could be squeezed by advancing
the pawns on the kingside.} 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. e5 Ne8 {Statically the position
looks good for Black - d5 currently belongs to his knights.} 18. Nb1 $1 {
This excellent manoeuvre poses Black concrete problems with defending the
c4-pawn.} Nc7 19. Na3 b5 {The only challenging move for White - Black relies
on his pawn majority.} 20. Bd2 $1 {A decent idea - White liquidates the most
active piece of his opponent.} Rad8 21. Bxb4 axb4 22. Nc2 $36 {The strong Bg2
offers White interesting compensation for the pawn.} *

