{[%evp 0,43,27,25,28,6,43,25,36,-7,-7,-7,2,1,9,-30,-1,-1,-3,-6,-18,-10,-1,-78,
-39,-29,-9,15,12,-1,10,20,48,41,46,38,70,58,50,65,64,70,70,69,63,63]} 1. d4 d5
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Nbd7 {In similar to the main
line 6...Bg7 and 7...Ne4, this move is mainly aimed for defending the Pc4.
However, it takes few tempi and allows White to quickly take the upper hand in
the centre.} 7. Qc2 Nb6 ({After} 7... b5 $6 8. Ne5 Bb7 9. b3 $16 {White will
get the pawn back, while ...b7-b5 made Black's position very dicey.}) 8. e4 Bg7
({After} 8... Bg4 $6 9. Be3 Bg7 {Adibekian,R - Jentsch,D Wesel Undeloh 2015} {
The simplest is} 10. Nbd2 $146 O-O 11. h3 Be6 12. Ng5 $16) 9. a4 a5 {This move
is practically forced.} ({Pointless is} 9... O-O $6 10. a5 Nbd7 11. Rd1 $16 {
The Pc4 will fall soon, and Nd7-b6 turns a loss of time.}) 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Na3
{There are few good-looking alternatives at White's disposal, but I like this
move: if the Pc4 falls, the Nd7-b6 manoevre will be pointless.} Be6 ({The
exchange of Bc8 is another concession:} 11... Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 $16 {
Nikologorskiy,K - Grachev,B St Petersburg 2012}) ({The prophylactic} 11... h6 {
vacates e6 for the bishop, but weakens the k-side, and after} 12. h3 Be6 13.
Ne5 Ne8 14. f4 $36 {White can start advancing his k-side pawns, and the Ne5 is
stable. Cori,J - Rambaldi,F New York 2018}) 12. h3 Ne8 ({It makes a little
sense to attack the Ph3:} 12... Qc8 13. Kh2 Rd8 14. Be3 $16 {Black's pieces
were misplaced, and the Pc4 seems to fall anyways. Eljanov,P - Ramirez Alvarez,
A Chess.com INT 2019}) 13. Ng5 Bc8 ({After} 13... Bxd4 14. Be3 c5 15. Nb5 $16 {
Black's will be left without his main defender.}) 14. Nxc4 {Eventually White
took the pawn in favorable situation.} Nxc4 15. Qxc4 e5 {Only this break might
offer Black some counter-play.} 16. Nf3 {The knight did its job, and now it is
coming back to make g5 vacant for the bishop.} exd4 {This was Ding,L - Giri,A
Shenzhen 2017} {I can present the following valuable novelty:} 17. Bg5 $1 $146
({Instead,} 17. Nxd4 $6 Be6 18. Qd3 Nc7 {allows Black to mibilize his forces
and equalize.}) 17... Qd6 ({After} 17... Be6 18. Bxd8 Bxc4 19. Be7 Be2 20. Rd2
Bxf3 21. Bxf3 $16 {there is no real compensation for an exchange.}) 18. Nxd4
Nc7 19. Nf5 $1 {This is the best way to make use of promising opposition along
the d-file.} Qe6 20. Nh6+ Bxh6 21. Qxe6 Bxe6 22. Bxh6 $16 {The strong
unopposite Bh6 makes Black's position hughly unpleasant.} *

