1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. a4 O-O {
This natural move was made by many strong players, such as Anand, Nepomniatchi,
Malakhov and others. However, I find it less challenging than 7...Ne4: it
allows White to immediately regain the pawn in a favourable situation.} ({
Worth attention is} 7... Be6 8. Ng5 Bd5 $146 {Curiously, this natural move has
never been tried yet.} ({Less consistent is} 8... Bd7 9. Na3 h6 10. Nf3 Be6 11.
Ne5 {Eventually the c4-pawn will fall.} Bd5 {This was Vignesh,N - Paravyan,D
Moscow 2014. There was nothing wrong with} 12. Naxc4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 O-O 14. f3
Nbd7 15. e4 $14 {White has a clear positional edge due to his strong centre.})
({Black can hardly fight for equality with} 8... Qd7 9. Nxe6 Qxe6 10. Na3 {
The Qe6 is awkwardly placed and the c4-pawn should fall sooner or later anyway.
} O-O 11. Qc2 Na6 12. e3 $14 {Rawlings,A - Kazoks,A ICCF email 2012}) 9. f3 $1
{This quiet move secures White a strong pawn centre.} ({Instead, after} 9. e4
h6 10. exd5 hxg5 11. dxc6 Nxc6 {the open h-file offers Black definite
counterplay.}) 9... h6 10. Nh3 {The Ng5 has done its job.} O-O 11. e4 Be6 12.
Be3 a5 {Fixing the b4-spot is a slight achievement here.} 13. Nf4 Bc8 14. Na3
$14) ({Another somewhat artificial continuation,} 7... Na6 {, was tried twice
by opening expert GM Volokitin.} 8. Na3 Be6 9. Ng5 Qd7 10. Nxe6 Qxe6 11. e3 $1
{A solid choice. The d4-pawn is secured and White can attack the c4-pawn soon.}
Ne4 {Dubov,D - Volokitin,A Batumi 2018} 12. Nxc4 $146 Qxc4 13. Bxe4 O-O 14. b3
